<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sharks Head Home Down 3-2 to Avs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Down 3-2 in their first-round playoff  
series to the Colorado Avalanche, the San Jose Sharks return to the 
San Jose Arena where they lost the first two games of this 
postseason series. 
</P>
<P>
	Down 0-2 in this delayed series, the Sharks then won the next  
two at Denver before the Avalanche came back to take Saturday 
night's game 6-2 at home. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sharks got what they needed in Colorado: a chance to bring  
the best-of-seven series back to California. If the Sharks win on 
Monday night, Game 7 will be played back in Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Sharks have a daunting task. They are underdogs to the  
Avalanche no matter where they play. 
</P>
<P>
	``We weren't happy with our performance, but we came in and won  
two out of three and kept the series alive,'' San Jose forward Jeff 
Friesen said. ``We take the series back to the Shark Tank and will 
go back to work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Center Mike Ricci agreed. Perhaps the home-ice advantage would  
work in San Jose's favor this time. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's still a lot of hockey to be played,'' Ricci said.  
``This wasn't their fourth win and that's the positive. They need 
four wins and we need four wins. All we're thinking about right now 
is getting three.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sharks also face a suddenly rejuvenated Theo Fleury, who was  
fairly quiet early in the playoffs but came back with two goals and 
an assist Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just a matter of time,'' Fleury said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Avalanche, however, weren't looking past Monday's game  
despite their advantages, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a long ways from over,'' he said. ``They're going to  
bring their best game Monday. ... We've got one hockey game to win, 
and it's the hardest one to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sharks coach Darryl Sutter gambled and put Steve Shields in goal  
Saturday, giving Mike Vernon a night off. Vernon has won Stanley 
Cups with Calgary and Detroit over the course of his career, but 
Shields was hot down the stretch of the regular season, going 9-0-2 
in his last 11 starts. 
</P>
<P>
	Sutter wasn't about to second-guess himself after the Game 5  
loss. Because of the delayed schedule, Vernon, 36, was facing a 
possible seven games in 11 nights. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was probably going to have one bad night if he did that, so  
we're probably better off that this was how it turned out,'' Sutter 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The series was supposed to have started in Denver, but was  
delayed because of the mass shooting at Columbine High School. 
Instead, the first two games were played in San Jose. 
</P>
<P>
	Vernon, no doubt, will be back for Game 6. He wasn't dwelling on  
what might have been, had he been in goal Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's why it's called a team game,'' he said. ``Everybody  
contributes. We just weren't prepared as a team tonight. Now we 
have to regroup.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
