<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 17:51:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Girl's 'Petworld' Game Gets Licensed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Creativity, faith and a lot of hard work let  
11-year-old Casey Smith parlay an elementary school project into a 
board game that will soon be sold in major stores nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Casey used magic markers and cardboard three years ago to create  
Casey's Petworld -- a Monopoly-style board game in which players 
collect, and sometimes lose, money and pets -- as a classroom 
project. Her mother, an artist, helped with the graphics. 
</P>
<P>
	The invention changed the lives of Casey -- short for Cassandra --  
and her mother, LeAnn, forever. 
</P>
<P>
	The Minneapolis girl, with mother in tow, spent four days at the  
American International Toy Fair in February helping Cadaco Inc., a 
Chicago game manufacturer, introduce the game to big-name toy 
retailers. 
</P>
<P>
	For Casey, a fifth-grader, that meant long days in the Cadaco  
booth talking with retail buyers and a news conference where she 
showed off her invention to the media. 
</P>
<P>
	``She did the whole spiel, showed them how it was played, did  
the sales speech. She was at the booth most times from 8 o'clock in 
the morning to 5 o'clock. She was a pro,'' her proud mother said. 
</P>
<P>
	Casey said the fair was fun.  
</P>
<P>
	``People were real supportive. They thought it was great. The  
other inventors came by and said, 'You've done a great job with 
this,' '' Casey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith became the backstage mom after she and her daughter  
licensed Petworld to Cadaco for manufacture and distribution. 
Cadaco is rolling out the game nationally the first week of May to 
coincide with Be Kind to Animals Week. 
</P>
<P>
	The company already has Petworld orders from FAO Schwartz, Zany  
Brainy, Learning Express, some Target stores and specialty toy 
stores, said Don Light, Cadaco's national sales manager. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every year there's probably hundreds of board game invention  
opportunities for big companies. Very few actually get to market,'' 
Light said. ``This is one of the few that actually made it through 
everything and made it to market. That's a real accomplishment for 
Casey.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Casey, who has two rats, a bird, a cat and fish at home, built  
the game around her favorite subject -- pets. Petworld, intended for 
young school-age children, incorporates reading, counting, 
exchanging money and learning pet responsibilities. 
</P>
<P>
	The Smiths were on their own when they took Petworld to the  
Javits trade show during the New York Toy Fair in February 1998, 
manufacturing the game in small numbers and doing their own sales 
and marketing from home. 
</P>
<P>
	They caught the eye of George Oess, Cadaco's president.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're a privately owned smaller company ourselves. We live by  
our wits so I like to look for things that already have had a 
little bit of success,'' Oess said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also liked the story behind Petworld.  
</P>
<P>
	Smith, a single mom, quit her job as a salad and sandwich chef  
and borrowed $30,000 from friends and family to put the game on the 
market. On their own, the Smiths had sold about 4,500 games at 
small specialty stores around the country and locally through two 
major retailers. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said she didn't have the money to properly market the  
game, so she decided to team with Cadaco, a 64-year-old company 
that could do the job. The deal also would enable Smith to pursue 
her own interest in computer graphics. 
</P>
<P>
	Petworld was licensed to Cadaco for a guaranteed royalty on  
sales and a lump sum, ``which took the company pretty much out of 
debt,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thinking about the bills that I owed was really hard on me.  
That was one of the reasons that it was licensed,'' Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cadaco is doing a first production run of 10,000 games, and  
plans three or four runs before Christmas. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel if we give this game a lot of nurturing, Casey could  
have a best-selling game sold throughout the United States,'' Oess 
said. Cadaco has low overhead and can stay with a game that might 
take a while to catch on, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Oess said the game plays well and the topic is timeless.  
</P>
<P>
	``For us, that's better than looking for something that's going  
to be here today, gone tomorrow,'' he said. ``It's not often that a 
little girl creates something that becomes commercially successful. 
We've got pretty high hopes that it will.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Casey encourages other kids to put their own imaginations to  
work, because ``you never can tell where your ideas might take you. 
If you have what it takes and you have a strong will, go for it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
