<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Meets on Olympic Ethics Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- An eight-member ethics panel,  
including former Senate Majority leader Howard Baker and former 
U.N. chief Javier Perez de Cuellar, prepared Sunday for the first 
of a series of meetings intended to clean up the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The ethics commission was established last month in response to  
the Salt Lake City bribery scandal, in which 10 International 
Olympic Committee members were expelled or resigned for receiving 
improper inducements during the campaign to win the right to stage 
the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	It is meant to help the IOC study the Olympic bidding and  
selection process, ensure accountability and enforce compliance 
with a new code of conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission will report the outcome of its opening  
discussions Monday to an IOC executive board meeting the following 
day. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the items up for discussion will likely be the fate of  
Australian IOC member Phil Coles, who has already received a ``most 
severe warning'' from the IOC for receiving travel and 
accommodation perks from Salt Lake City. He is under renewed 
scrutiny since his ex-wife claimed that members of Athens 
unsuccessful bid for the 1996 Olympics gave her jewelry. 
</P>
<P>
	It may also discuss the case of South Korean executive board  
member Kim Un-yong, who also received a ``most severe warning'' and 
is the highest-ranking official implicated. Kim could face 
expulsion if the IOC proves he knew that the Salt Lake committee 
paid for his son's salary at a telecommunications company. 
</P>
<P>
	The ethics committee is chaired by IOC vice president Keba Mbaye  
of Senegal, a former vice president of the International Court of 
Justice. The other members are French Sen. Robert Badinter, former 
Swiss President Kurt Furgler, former Canadian Olympic athlete 
Charmaine Crooks and IOC executive board members Kevan Gosper of 
Australia and Chiharu Igaya of Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker was a member of the U.S. Senate from 1967-85 and Perez de  
Cuellar was U.N. chief from 1982-91. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
