<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dole Takes Centrist Gun Control View </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole staked out a centrist  
position on gun control, setting her apart from most of the GOP 
presidential field, as eight Republican candidates tried Sunday 
night to take advantage of George W. Bush's absence from New 
Hampshire's unofficial kickoff to the 2000 primary season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think you need an AK-47 to defend your family,'' Mrs.  
Dole said, receiving a smattering of polite applause. The reception 
was even cooler when the former American Red Cross president said 
she supported child safety locks on handguns. 
</P>
<P>
	One crowd member booed. Few applauded.  
</P>
<P>
	And in what aides said what challenge to the National Rifle  
Association, a powerful GOP-leaning lobby, Mrs. Dole promised she 
would be tough on crime ``no matter what the special interests 
say.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The state GOP dinner, which drew 1,200 party activists, was  
billed as the first major Republican event of the 2000 campaign in 
this first-in-the-nation primary state. 
</P>
<P>
	Three likely candidates failed to attend: Arizona Sen. John  
McCain, TV commentator Pat Buchanan and Bush. McCain was 
celebrating his son's 13th birthday; Buchanan was campaigning in 
Arizona; Bush, Texas' governor, has refused to campaign outside his 
state until the legislative session ends later this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	Many activists who attended the kickoff questioned or criticized  
Bush's decision to pass up the event. Yet most predicted it would 
not change his front-runner status. 
</P>
<P>
	For the rest of field, the gathering offered a chance to shine  
outside Bush's shadow. Their goal is to emerge as alternative pick 
should Bush falter. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole's was the boldest attempt at creating news and drawing  
attention to her campaign. Wearing a clip-on microphone, she stood 
several feet from the podium -- spinning on her high heels to 
address the crowd that surrounded her. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she supports the continuation of the assault-weapons  
ban, elimination of bullets that pierce bulletproof vests and full 
federal funding of instant background checks for gun buyers. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole's remarks seemed designed to bolster her standing as  
the No. 2 Republican candidate in national polls; restrictions on 
the availability of guns are popular among independent and moderate 
voters, especially women. 
</P>
<P>
	The gun debate has heated up in the wake of the Colorado school  
shootings, a tragedy mentioned by several of the GOP hopefuls. Gun 
control is a prickly issue for Republican candidates because 
conservative voters tend to oppose it, particularly in an 
independent-minded state like New Hampshire, and the National Rifle 
Association is a powerful lobby. 
</P>
<P>
	Typical of the GOP field was Steve Forbes, who wandered a foot  
or two from the podium to say the Littleton, Colo., shootings show 
that people are capable of ``great good and great evil.'' Yet, in 
stark contrast to Mrs. Dole, he said the country must ``resist the 
temptation to enact new laws'' in response to such tragedies. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Vice President Dan Quayle, avoiding the gun debate,  
argued that he deserves the nomination. ``Who has been fighting for 
your values and your families for over 20 years? Who has the 
experience when it comes to foreign policy and who has been tested 
and has the courage to lead this great country of ours?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. John Kasich of Ohio portrayed himself as the candidate who  
would ease ``the frustrations of everyday working people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Bob Smith, a native son with little chance of winning the  
nomination, bragged that he voted to impeach President Clinton and 
attacked Republicans who didn't. 

</P>
<P>
	By challening the NRA, Mrs. Dole adopted a strategy used by  
President Clinton in the 1996 presidential campaign to court 
moderate voters from both parties. Aides say they were not troubled 
by the cool reaction Sunday because Mrs. Dole is trying to expand 
the party's base by targeting moderate voters, not party regulars. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush has struggled to make his position on gun control clear,  
though he says he supports instant checks on weapons bought at gun 
shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole's rivals said the school shootings are a symptom of  
declining values. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Tennesse Gov. Lamar Alexander, promising to make raising  
children easier if elected, said ``the culture is tougher. It's 
getting harder to grow up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Conservative activist Gary Bauer, who announced his candidacy  
the day after the shootings, said America is a great country, ``but 
if we do not remember that America was built on God ... nothing 
else will matter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With a wide lead in polls, it seems Bush can afford to miss an  
opportunity to court New Hampshire Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a chance to show a lot of people that he is for  
real,'' said Ron Woermer, 51, a Nashua, N.H., marketing director. 
Still, he is open to backing Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``Looks like a winner, doesn't he?'' Woermer said with a smile.  
</P>
</TEXT>
