<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Entrapment' Nabs Top Film Spot / Box Office  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Powered by sexual chemistry, exotic locations  
and Sean Connery's roguish charm, the cat-burglar thriller 
``Entrapment'' nabbed the top spot at the weekend box office with 
$20.7 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The film, starring Catherine Zeta-Jones as an insurance  
investigator who seduces a high-class art thief played by Connery, 
knocked ``The Matrix'' down to No. 2 with $8.7 million, industry 
estimates showed Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Entrapment'' benefited from strong advertising in which a  
leotard-clad Zeta-Jones slinks through a web of laser beams and 
Connery performs stunts reminiscent of his days as James Bond, said 
Robert Bucksbaum, a movie analyst with Reel Source Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sean Connery has been around forever and has a lot of star  
power. Adult women wanted to see him, and young men wanted to see 
her,'' he said. ``It had all the elements of a hit written all over 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The horror-comedy ``Idle Hands,'' the only other film opening in  
wide release this weekend, grossed a disappointing $1.8 million, 
tying for sixth place with ``10 Things I Hate About You.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The story of a pot-smoking teen who slays his friends because a  
demon has possessed his hand may have suffered from macabre 
comparisons to the killings at Columbine High School in Littleton, 
Colo., Bucksbaum said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They may have backed off a little on their marketing campaign  
because teen-agers killing other teens would have turned off a lot 
of people,'' he said. ``People didn't feel like seeing a movie like 
this so close to that incident.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Comedies dominated the rest of the top 10, with the Eddie  
Murphy-Martin Lawrence prison movie ``Life'' earning $6.4 million 
for third place. 
</P>
<P>
	The Drew Barrymore high school comedy ``Never Been Kissed''  
continued to do well but dropped to fourth place with $4.2 million, 
while the mobster-in-therapy movie ``Analyze This'' fell to fifth 
with $2.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Having already grossed $98.5 million, ``Analyze This'' has  
inched its way toward becoming the second film of 1999 to cross the 
$100 million mark. The first was ``The Matrix,'' which has earned 
$129.7 million. 
</P>
<P>
	After a disappointing opening, two other comedies plummeted to  
the bottom of the top 10 in only their second week of release. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pushing Tin,'' starring John Cusack and Billy Bob Thornton as  
frantic air traffic controllers, earned $1.3 million for eighth 
place. ``Lost &AMP; Found,'' featuring David Spade as a smarmy 
dognapper, opened in ninth place with $1.28 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Weekend ticket sales were 4.5 percent higher than the same  
weekend last year, when ``Titanic'' dropped out of the top 5 
movies. 
</P>
<P>
	Estimated grosses for Friday through Sunday at North American  
theaters, according to Exhibitor Relations Inc., with final figures 
to be released Monday: 
</P>
<P>
	1. ``Entrapment,'' $20.7 million.  
</P>
<P>
	2. ``The Matrix,'' $8.7 million.  
</P>
<P>
	3. ``Life,'' $6.4 million.  
</P>
<P>
	4. ``Never Been Kissed,'' $4.2 million.  
</P>
<P>
	5. ``Analyze This,'' $2.2 million.  
</P>
<P>
	6. ``10 Things I Hate About You,'' $1.8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	6. ``Idle Hands,'' $1.8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	8. ``Pushing Tin,'' $1.3 million.  
</P>
<P>
	9. ``Lost &AMP; Found,'' $1.28 million.  
</P>
<P>
	10. ``Go,'' $1.2 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
