<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990502.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 15:44:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Bulls Bask in Win Over Miami Heat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- It's easy to imagine the reaction by M.J., Scottie  
and the Worm when they saw the score. 
</P>
<P>
	Dumbfounded disbelief. And then delight.  
</P>
<P>
	Michael Jordan and company always loved to beat the Heat, and  
that's what the Chicago Bulls did Saturday. The defending NBA 
champions lived up to their billing for a change by shocking Miami 
101-86. 
</P>
<P>
	The Heat were without Alonzo Mourning, sidelined by an eye  
injury, but so what? The Bulls were without Jordan, Scottie Pippen 
and Dennis Rodman. 
</P>
<P>
	``When M.J. calls, I'm going to say I know how he feels some  
nights,'' Bulls guard Ron Harper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Harper scored 25 points, all in the second half, and the team  
with the worst record in the Eastern Conference beat the 
first-place Heat, jumbling the playoff picture. 
</P>
<P>
	Mourning and coach Pat Riley watched from opposite ends of the  
Heat bench, mirror images of frustration. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not disappointed. I'm not discouraged. I'm just absolutely  
disgusted,'' Riley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami fans felt likewise. They expected the Bulls to play as  
poorly as that other dismantled championship team, the Florida 
Marlins. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, in keeping with spring tradition, Chicago dealt Miami  
another crushing defeat. The Heat have made the playoffs five 
times, and three times -- in 1992, 1996 and 1997 -- they were 
eliminated by Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Heat and Bulls go back years,'' Harper said. ``There have  
been a lot of hard-fought games, so this one feels good for all of 
us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The win left the Bulls a bit giddy in the locker room. Someone  
wrote ``Machine-Gun Harper'' on the blackboard. Toni Kukoc 
pretended to drink cologne in celebration. Dickey Simpkins became 
almost incoherent. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've lost games this season by a lot of money -- I mean  
points,'' Simpkins said. ``There's nothing better than beating 
Miami by double figures on their court at crunch time. We feel 
great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bulls started two obscure rookies and took the court with  
the worst offense in the NBA. They had scored a league record-low 
49 points in losing to Miami just three weeks earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	But by halftime, Chicago had 48 points -- and the lead. Sparked  
by Harper, they built the margin to 22 points in the third period 
and never faltered in the fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bulls repeatedly took advantage of Mourning's absence by  
driving inside, and then Harper got hot from the outside. After 
missing his only shot in the first half, he finished 9-for-14, 
including 4-for-7 from 3-point range. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I've seen Ron Harper play like that in a long  
time,'' Riley said. ``He was saving one for us, because he was 
absolutely extraordinary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bulls made half their shots for only the second time all  
season, sinking 58 percent, the best effort against Miami in 
Riley's four years as coach. Chicago exceeded its scoring average 
by 19 points and topped 100 for just the third time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Bulls fans enjoyed this game,'' Kukoc said with a  
broad grin, perhaps feeling the effects of the cologne. 
</P>
<P>
	Also happy were the Orlando Magic, Indiana Pacers and Atlanta  
Hawks, all trying to overtake Miami for the conference 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though we're not going to the playoffs, it's important to  
establish some momentum for next season,'' Simpkins said. ``Why not 
come in and mess up someone else's playoff chances and try to gain 
some respect at the same time?'' 
</P>
<P>
	So if Saturday's win wasn't exactly Game 7 of the NBA Finals, it  
was the Bulls' biggest victory since then. 
</P>
<P>
	``By far,'' Harper said. ``We enjoyed beating Miami.''  
</P>
<P>
	In Chicago, that's one thing that hasn't changed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
