<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Duke Not Ready To Throw in Towel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- It was supposed to be his last try at a  
political comeback. But David Duke, having fallen short by fewer 
than 4,000 votes in his bid for Bob Livingston's congressional 
seat, was unwilling to say ``never again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The former Ku Klux Klan leader and author of ``My Awakening,''  
an autobiographical call for ``Aryan revolution,'' told a crowd of 
about 150 disappointed supporters that he was not ready to fade 
away. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not ruling anything out for the rest of my life,'' he said  
during a grudging Saturday night concession speech. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke had said several times before Saturday's Louisiana  
elections that this would be his last campaign if he did not win. 
</P>
<P>
	Running as a Republican in Louisiana's unique open primary  
system, he came in third behind two of the state's GOP stalwarts: 
former Gov. Dave Treen, making his own political comeback 15 years 
after he left office; and David Vitter, a two-term state 
representative who won passage of a constitutional amendment 
limiting state legislators to three four-year terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Treen and Vitter will meet in a May 29 runoff to decide who will  
finish Livingston's term. Livingston was in line to become House 
Speaker after more than 20 years in Congress, but he abruptly 
announced his resignation in December after confessing to marital 
infidelities. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Republican Congressional Committee is relieved that  
Duke was rejected, said its chairman, Rep. Tom Davis, R-Va. ``He's 
out of it, thank goodness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was Duke's best showing since the 1991 governor's race, when  
he displaced faltering incumbent Buddy Roemer and won a runoff spot 
against three-term former Gov. Edwin Edwards. Edwards trounced Duke 
in the runoff and Duke's political fortunes fell precipitously with 
a weak run for the Republican presidential nomination, an abandoned 
try for governor in 1995 and a fourth-place showing in the 1996 
U.S. Senate race. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Duke benefited from a relatively light turnout of  
about 36 percent and a splintered vote among the seven Republicans 
and two Democrats, all conservatives. He also was buoyed by white 
middle-class voters who feel threatened by affirmative action. 
</P>
<P>
	``He ran much better than I thought he would. He ran much better  
than everyone thought he would,'' said Wayne Parent, political 
scientist at Louisiana State University. 
</P>
<P>
	Complete but unofficial returns showed Treen with 36,547 votes,  
or 25 percent, and Vitter with 31,652 votes, or 22 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke had 27,967 votes, or 19 percent. Ophthalmologist Monica  
Monica, also a Republican, received 22,855 votes, or 16 percent. 
State Rep. Bill Strain, a Democrat, received 16,372 votes, or 11 
percent. Four other candidates split the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	Most polls had shown Duke with no more than 10 percent support,  
demonstrating Duke's oft-repeated campaign mantra: ``I fly under 
radar,'' meaning his supporters are reluctant to acknowledge their 
choice to pollsters. 
</P>
<P>
	That was evidenced even by one of the 150 who attended his  
would-be victory party Saturday night in suburban Metairie. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharon, who would not give her last name, confessed to some  
discomfort with Duke's KKK history. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't entirely trust him, but a lot of the things he says I  
do support,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's victors promised a clean campaign -- unlike the final  
days before the runoff, when each was drawn into a vitriolic series 
of attack and counterattack ads. Treen turns 71 in July and Vitter 
has said the ex-governor is ``biologically term-limited.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
