<DOCNO> APW19990502.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 11:32:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heston Says Gun Laws Not Answer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- National Rifle Association President Charlton  
Heston said Sunday that better pursuit of criminals, not new gun 
laws, is the best way to prevent a repeat of the Colorado high 
school shootings. An administration proposal to impose new 
background checks on gun purchasers, he said, ``smells of 
tyranny.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Heston, in his first national interview since the shootings at  
Columbine High School, told ABC's ``This Week'' that he would also 
oppose President Clinton's attempt to limit handgun purchases to 
one a month. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before you know it, it becomes no guns,'' he said, emphasizing  
the NRA argument that gun control advocates are trying to build up 
momentum for more comprehensive restrictions on gun ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	The NRA has been on the defensive since two teenagers killed 12  
students and a teacher at the Denver area high school before 
committing suicide. Some 8,000 people demonstrated outside an NRA 
annual convention in Denver Saturday to decry the NRA's hard-line 
positions on gun ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	But Heston insisted that ``the problem is not the availability  
of guns,'' but the failure of the Justice Department to enforce 
what he said are more than 2,000 laws controlling the sale and 
ownership of firearms. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not interested in denying them purchase,'' the former  
actor said of convicted felons, who would be targeted by Clinton's 
proposal to extend waiting periods included in the Brady Law. ``I'm 
interested in seeing them imprisoned. There are plenty of laws to 
do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, in the most far-ranging gun-control package since the  
Brady Law passed five years ago, is seeking to raise the legal age 
for handgun possession from 18 to 21, hold negligent parents 
liable, halt imports of all high-capacity ammunition clips and 
limit handgun purchases to one a month. 
</P>
<P>
	He would also mandate child-safety locks on all guns sold,  
impose background checks on buyers for all gun-show sales, and 
require a three-day waiting period for all handgun purchases. Today 
most checks to verify that a would-be purchaser doesn't have a 
criminal record are done instantaneously. 
</P>
<P>
	``How can anyone say that those requirements are not  
reasonable?'' said Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder, also on 
ABC. 
</P>
<P>
	Holder rejected the NRA's ``slippery slope'' argument, saying  
that in five years the Brady Law, which requires background checks, 
has prevented 250,000 people with criminal records from getting 
guns while people's legitimate rights to buy guns have not ``been 
restricted in any kind of major way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton package faces an uphill fight in Congress, where the  
Republican majority has long been suspicious of gun control, and 
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., echoed Heston in saying 
the answer to youth violence lies in better enforcement rather than 
more laws. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think when you commit a crime with a gun, we ought to throw  
the book at them, and we ought to enforce those laws, and the 
Justice Department has not been doing that,'' he said on CNN's 
``Late Edition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, on ``Fox News  
Sunday,'' said that since Clinton took office, gun violation 
prosecutions have been cut in half. ``This administration hasn't 
been very serious about guns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., a leading advocate of gun control,  
praised the Clinton package but acknowledged that even passing 
modest new laws will be tough. One survey found that only 4 percent 
of Americans think new gun control laws aren't needed, he said, and 
``I think that 4 percent is all in the Congress.' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
