<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 09:14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y. To Allow E-Mail Prescriptions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Xjkdfvdsgasdfadstfhfbdfg.  
</P>
<P>
	That's what most people -- and some pharmacists -- see on their  
prescription after a doctor scribbles the name of a type of pill on 
a pad. 
</P>
<P>
	But starting in June, a doctor's bad handwriting won't matter  
because New York state will allow e-mail and fax communication 
between a physician and a pharmacist. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, New York bans doctors from faxing or e-mailing their  
patients' prescriptions to a pharmacy, although 40 states allow 
prescriptions to be faxes and 30 allow them to be e-mailed. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new regulations, however, controlled substances will  
not be able to be prescribed electronically. 
</P>
<P>
	Joining the computer and fax age will virtually eliminate the  
possibility of a pharmacist giving someone the wrong medicine 
because of a misunderstanding caused by the doctor's handwriting or 
a mispronunciation over the phone, Regents Chancellor Carl Hayden 
said April 27. 
</P>
<P>
	``The move to that form could eliminate 40 percent of  
prescription errors,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Within three years, half of the prescriptions will be handled  
electronically,'' Hayden predicted. At least 165 million 
prescriptions are written each year in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Representatives of doctors and pharmacists' organizations said  
they don't have any problem with the new regulations, which will 
take effect June 18. 
</P>
<P>
	An e-mail or a fax ``certainly would be easier to decipher than  
it is to decipher someone's handwriting,'' said Craig Burridge, 
executive director of the Pharmacists Society of the State of New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	Information will be encrypted to prevent unauthorized access to  
patient information, officials said. Unauthorized access by a 
pharmacist could result in the loss of a license and possible 
criminal prosecution, according to Hayden and state Education 
Commissioner Robert Mills. 
</P>
<P>
	The Board of Regents, which supervises public and private  
education in New York state, also licenses pharmacists, among other 
professionals. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors and pharmacists going online shouldn't increase the  
costs of their services, officials said. ``Pharmacies are 98 
percent electronic anyway,'' Burridge said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new regulations also require pharmacists to personally offer  
counseling about medication when prescriptions are filled or 
refilled instead of allowing unlicensed personnel like cashiers to 
do it. 
</P>
<P>
	Requiring pharmacists to talk to people about their medication  
will decrease the chance that people will take medicines that react 
badly to each other, Mills said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new rules also allow patients to authorize the electronic  
sharing of their personal medical profile between pharmacies. That 
will allow patients to get their prescriptions filled or refilled 
at any pharmacy in the state or potentially the nation, officials 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
