<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Elder Runner Sets World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- A 96-year-old man shattered an age-group world  
record Saturday when he ran the 100-meter dash in 24.01 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Erwin Jaskulski of Honolulu broke the 95-and-older age-group  
record of 38.82 seconds set by Kazuhiko Tsutsumi of Japan in 1997, 
said officials at the Punahou Relays. 
</P>
<P>
	Jaskulski broke the world record twice last year, but his  
efforts weren't recognized by the World Association of Veteran 
Athletes because of technical questions about wind and the lack of 
electronic timing equipment, the officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	All requirements were met for Saturday's race, said meet referee  
Gordon Scruton Sr. 
</P>
<P>
	``This record has to be accepted by WAVA,'' said Jack Karbens,  
president of the Hawaii Masters Track Club. ``Everything was in 
place to meet all the requirements, including adequate officials, 
electronic timing and wind gauges. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is our hope that Erwin Jaskulski can finally take his  
recognized place as the world's fastest human in his age group,'' 
Karbens said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990502.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 18:21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marlins' Fernandez Goes Back on DL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Florida Marlins pitcher Alex Fernandez is going  
back on the disabled list, this time with a pulled groin muscle. 
</P>
<P>
	In his fourth start of the year -- his second since returning  
from the DL -- Fernandez left in the second inning with a pulled 
right groin and will go on the disabled list Monday. He winced in 
pain after throwing a pitch to Tony Eusebio, coming off the mound 
awkwardly. 
</P>
<P>
	``To be honest, I'm happy it's not his shoulder,'' Florida  
manager John Boles said. ``When I went out to the mound I thought 
'Oh gosh, this is his career.' But it was his groin ... so right 
away it wasn't an uplifting experience, but it was better than it 
could have been.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez, who missed the entire 1998 season following surgery  
to repair a torn rotator cuff, will be examined Monday by Dr. Dan 
Kanell to determine the severity of the latest injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's part of the game,'' Fernandez said as he leaned on  
crutches. ``What I've gone through and endured over the last 18 
months is a lot more than a groin pull.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez's first trip to the DL this year was caused by  
inflammation in the shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't see the life on his fastball,'' said Houston's Bill  
Spiers. ``I know him from the American League and I know how he 
used to throw, but he's coming back from a serious injury. It's a 
long road.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez, who threw four shutout innings last Tuesday against  
the Cubs, said his shoulder felt strong Sunday. He also said the 
time off rehabilitating the groin might help the shoulder too. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess you have to try and find the positive,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Florida will put Fernandez on the 15-day disabled list Monday  
and bring up reliever Rafael Medina from Triple-A Calgary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
