<DOCNO> APW19990502.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 18:41:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jockey Hurt After Setting Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just one race after guiding Artax to a track  
record, jockey Jorge Chavez was involved in a nasty spill at 
Aqueduct on Sunday, but was not seriously injured. 
</P>
<P>
	In the eighth race, the $200,000 Grade I Carter Handicap, Artax  
and Chavez set a track record, covering seven furlongs in 1:20:04. 
</P>
<P>
	In the ninth and final race, a seven-furlong allowance, Coby  
Appeal, who raced wide from the start, fell, tossing Chavez to the 
track. 
</P>
<P>
	Remsenberg, ridden by Shaun Bridgmohan, instinctively leaped  
over the fallen Coby Appeal causing the jockey to lose his balance 
and fall. Both Coby Appeal and Remsenberg appeared to have escaped 
serious injury as they ran riderless from the site of the mishap. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez, 37, was taken from the track on a stretcher and then by  
ambulance to North Shore University Hospital in Manhasset, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	He was examined, evaluated and released, a community relations  
spokeswoman for the hospital said Sunday night. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a jockey's room attendant, Chavez was complaining  
of shoulder soreness when he was taken to the ambulance. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Depass, Chavez's agent, said the rider bit his tongue  
and lost his helmet during the spill. 
</P>
<P>
	Bridgmohan got up immediately and, though shaken up, spoke only  
of experiencing some stiffness. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez, a native of Peru, was the leading rider in New York from  
1994 through 1997. In 1997 he finished 10th in the nation in 
earnings with more than $9 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The track record Artax broke was set by Dr. Fager on Nov. 2,  
1968 in the Vosburgh Handicap. Dr. Fager was clocked in 1:20:20 but 
he carried 139 pounds, 25 more than Artax did. 
</P>
<P>
	Affirmed Success finished 3 1/4 lengths behind Artax and 2 1/2 lengths  
in front of Western Borders in the field of nine. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second time in the last three years Chavez rode the  
winner of the Carter as he guided Langfuhr to the winner's circle 
in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The win was the first in six starts this year for Artax, a  
4-year-old colt by Marquetry from the Apalachee mare, Raging 
Apalachee. 
</P>
<P>
	Artax returned $12.20, $5.40 and $4.40. Affirmed Success paid  
$3.50 and $2.80, while Western Borders was $8.60 to show. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990502.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 17:14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Grissom's Mercury Capsule Located </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Lost at sea for 38 years, astronaut  
Gus Grissom's Mercury capsule was found over the weekend by an 
underwater salvage team that had been searching for the spacecraft 
300 miles offshore. 
</P>
<P>
	Liberty Bell 7 is still 3 miles deep in the Atlantic.  
</P>
<P>
	The cable to a remotely operated rover used to identify and  
photograph the capsule snapped Saturday night because of the rough 
sea, and the rover sank. The salvagers are returning to Port 
Canaveral for new equipment and will have to wait several weeks 
before going back to recover the spacecraft. 
</P>
<P>
	But at least they know now where it is and they're thrilled  
about Saturday's discovery. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks to be in beautiful condition and certainly capable of  
being recovered,'' expedition leader Curt Newport said Sunday by 
phone from the ship, the Needham Tide. 
</P>
<P>
	The only U.S. spacecraft ever lost following a successful  
mission, the capsule is still shiny in spots with an intact window 
and the name ``Liberty Bell 7'' clearly printed beneath it. Even 
the fake crack that was painted on the exterior to replicate the 
real Liberty Bell is still visible, as are the singe marks left by 
the explosives that blew out the hatch following splashdown on July 
21, 1961. 
</P>
<P>
	Liberty Bell 7 sank following Grissom's successful 15-minute  
suborbital flight -- the nation's second manned space shot. The 
explosive bolts for blowing open the hatch detonated prematurely, 
and helicopter rescuers were unable to lift the waterlogged 
spacecraft from the sea. 
</P>
<P>
	Grissom nearly drowned, but was pulled to safety. He insisted  
until his death in the Apollo launch pad fire in 1967 that he'd 
done nothing wrong, although some questioned at the time -- and 
still do -- whether he bumped something or even panicked. 
</P>
<P>
	Grissom's widow, Betty, who feels certain the hatch  
malfunctioned, said last month that she hoped her husband's capsule 
would remain buried in the Atlantic. She resents not being 
consulted from the start about the salvage effort and does not want 
the spacecraft to be restored by the Kansas Cosmosphere and Space 
Center, as is the plan. That's where the capsule eventually will be 
put on display under an agreement with NASA and the Smithsonian 
Institution. 
</P>
<P>
	Newport's success didn't come easy.  
</P>
<P>
	He and his team ran into trouble after setting sail April 19 on  
a voyage financed by the Discovery Channel. The sonar promptly 
broke down. Once fixed, it uncovered 88 potential targets in the 
24-square-mile area that Newport pinpointed based on 14 years of 
studying NASA charts and interviewing those who were there when 
Liberty Bell 7 went down. 
</P>
<P>
	The first target they looked at with the camera-equipped rover  
ended up being the 7-foot titanium and aluminum capsule. 
</P>
<P>
	Newport said the team followed decomposed pieces of the  
capsule's heat shield up a hill. The trail of debris led to the 
capsule, propped upright. It emerged out of the gloom as a tall, 
conical, dark object; Newport thought at first it was airplane 
wreckage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember saying, 'Oh, my God, I can't believe it. That's it.  
We found it. This is it,' '' he said. ``There was a lot of shaking 
hands and slapping each other on the back and just congratulating 
each other and just staring in disbelief at this spacecraft in 
front of us, us being the first ones to see it since 1961.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newport, 47, had made two previous attempts to find the capsule.  
The former space station worker did not have sophisticated enough 
equipment or enough time during his tries in 1992 and 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was really a difficult thing to find,'' he noted. ``You  
have to understand, what we did was find something in water half a 
mile deeper than the Titanic and it's smaller than one of the 
Titanic's boilers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two cameras and a tape recorder that sank with the capsule could  
shed light on why the hatch blew open too soon -- one of the biggest 
mysteries of American space flight. It's doubtful, however, the 
film could be salvaged after so long underwater. 
</P>
<P>
	The hatch almost certainly would hold the answer. Newport  
estimates the hatch could be as much as a mile from Liberty Bell 7; 
he plans to spend a day looking for it when he returns for the 
capsule. 
</P>
<P>
	Before Newport and his team can recover the spacecraft and rover  
and search for the hatch, they must obtain another submersible like 
the one that sank Saturday. That will take at least a few weeks and 
possibly longer, said Mike Quattrone, senior vice president for the 
Discovery Channel, which is filming the expedition for a 
documentary to be broadcast this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are absolutely ecstatic,'' Quattrone said. ``When he gets  
back, I want to find out what kind of lucky charm he's carrying. To 
do this on the first dive is absolutely unheard of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the record, Newport's lucky charm is a stuffed lamb, one of  
his dog's favorite toys. It's on the ocean floor attached to the 
rover that sank, so Newport will have to wait a while before he 
gets it back. 
</P>
