<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Freed US POWs Reach Germany  
</P>
<P>
	RAMSTEIN, Germany (AP) -- After being held as prisoners of war in  
Yugoslavia for more than a month, three U.S. soldiers marched into 
freedom today. The jubilant servicemen arrived at a U.S. military 
base in southwest Germany, capping an emotional day-long journey by 
land and air from Yugoslavia's capital with the Rev. Jesse Jackson, 
who orchestrated their release in Belgrade. But there were no signs 
that the soldiers' release would bring an end to the NATO bombing 
of Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	Moscoso Wins Panama Presidency  
</P>
<P>
	PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) -- Mireya Moscoso, the widow of a  
popular leader, was elected today as the president who will lead 
Panama when the United States cedes control of the Panama Canal at 
the end of the year. She defeated Martin Torrijos, the son of 
military strongman Gen. Omar Torrijos, who had helped depose 
Moscoso's late husband from the presidency and went on to sign the 
1977 Canal Treaties with the United States. Moscoso's supporters 
drove through Panama City's streets, honking and waving her party's 
yellow, red and purple flags. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Refuses to Let Up Strikes  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A NATO spokesman said today there  
would be ``no reward'' for Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic 
for freeing three U.S. soldiers. ``What he's got to understand is 
that the decision that's going to impress us most is the decision 
to order troops out of Kosovo,'' and ``clearly and unambiguously'' 
accept an armed international force, said Jamie Shea, NATO's chief 
spokesman. The alliance launched the air campaign to force 
Milosevic to accept a peace deal for Kosovo, including widespread 
autonomy for the province and 28,000 NATO troops to enforce it. 

</P>
<P>
	IBM To Unveil Powerful Mainframe  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- IBM is set to debut tomorrow a new mainframe  
computer capable of processing 1.6 billion instructions per second, 
more than 50 percent more powerful than any machine on the market. 
The G6 is the first IBM mainframe to use the copper-semiconductor 
technology that the company introduced nearly two years ago. 
Analysts say that type of power could help online retailers, Web 
brokerages and other frequently overwhelmed e-businesses better 
handle the volume of transactions created by the explosion of 
demand from the Internet. 

</P>
<P>
	Climbers Say Body Found on Everest  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Members of an expedition seeking to determine  
whether Englishmen George Mallory and Andrew Irvine were the first 
to reach the summit of Mount Everest say they have located 
Mallory's body near the top of the world's highest peak. Eight 
climbers have been looking for the bodies of the men -- who 
disappeared in 1924 -- and a camera that could contain pictures 
proving they reached the summit 29 years before Sir Edmund Hillary 
and Sherpa Tenzing Norgay. 

</P>
<P>
	Colo. Students Attend Final Memorial  
</P>
<P>
	MORRISON, Colo. (AP) -- Columbine High School students and  
teachers today recounted bittersweet stories about their fallen 
friends at a final memorial service at the scenic Red Rocks 
amphitheater. The crowd was spared the rains that have deluged the 
area since shortly after the April 20 massacre of 12 students and 
one teacher at the Littleton high school. The gunmen behind the 
shooting and bombing spree committed suicide following the rampage. 
The students return to class tomorrow for the first time since the 
attack. They'll attend nearby Chatfield High School, their former 
rival. 

</P>
<P>
	7 Dead in Church Bus Crash  
</P>
<P>
	MAYHILL, N.M. (AP) -- A spare tire apparently fell today from a  
truck and smashed into a bus ferrying students from a church camp 
to their homes in Texas, killing seven people, state police said. 
``It just slid and just smashed into the bus,'' said Julie Selleck, 
who works at Pine Springs Summer Camp. The 2 p.m. crash on U.S. 82 
reportedly involved a semi-trailer, a motor home and the church 
bus, but that was not immediately confirmed, a state police 
spokesman said. 

</P>
<P>
	Cuban Team Arrives in Baltimore  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Cuba's national baseball team arrived in  
Baltimore tonight for an exhibition game tomorrow against the 
Orioles. The game marks the first time a Cuban team has played a 
major league team in the United States. Scott Kamieniecki will 
start for Baltimore. The Orioles can only hope the Cubans don't 
counter with Jose Contreras, who allowed two hits over eight 
shutout innings and struck out 10 the first time they met in March. 

</P>
<P>
	Bruins Beat Hurricanes 2-0  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Boston Bruins won their first playoff series  
in five years tonight, defeating the Carolina Hurricanes 2-0. Joe 
Thornton and Anson Carter scored as the Bruins completed their 
comeback from a 2-1 deficit by winning their third straight game 
and taking the best-of-7 Eastern Conference quarterfinal 4-2. Their 
second-round opponent depends on the outcome of other Eastern 
Conference series. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
</P>
</TEXT>
