<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Win Spots on U.S. Marathon Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Alfredo Vigueras won Sunday's U.S. men's  
marathon championship in 2:14:19, securing a spot on the team that 
will compete in the world championships in August. 
</P>
<P>
	Tatiana Titova, who splits training time between Russia and  
Gainesville, Fla., won the women's race at the UPMC Health System 
City of Pittsburgh Marathon in 2:39:59 
</P>
<P>
	Vigueras, 35, of Woodland, Calif., joins second-place finisher  
Eddy Hellebuyck of Albuquerque, N.M., and third-place Stephen Swift 
of Middletown, Conn., on the U.S. men's team, bound for the world 
marathon championship in Seville, Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	Hellebuyck, 38, a native of Belgium and 1996 Olympian who got  
his U.S. citizenship three weeks ago, finished in 2:16:58. Swift, 
28, beat his best-ever time by four minutes and finished the 
26.2-mile course in 2:17:26. 
</P>
<P>
	Vigueras, a substitute teacher who trained in Mexico, running  
his first marathon this year, won his first marathon by breaking 
away from the field at the 14th mile and catching Scott Larson at 
the 18th mile. 
</P>
<P>
	He finished 53 seconds behind his best marathon time, recorded  
in 1996 at Los Angeles. He said he had experienced lower back pain 
during the last three weeks and stomach and right leg pains during 
the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before the race, I was scared. But after a few miles, I forgot  
the pain and I concentrated on my job,'' Vigueras said. 
</P>
<P>
	During the race, Vigueras thought that Larson, who had pulled  
away from the field early and was running at 4:50 per mile with 
hired pacesetter Peter DeLaCerta, would falter. Larson eventually 
dropped out. 
</P>
<P>
	``When he took off, we knew he would either run the race or  
start dying. ... That was not a smart decision. You have to run a 
smart race to win this marathon,'' Vigueras said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he had been training with men 10 to 15 years younger in  
Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	``They gave me new energy,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Hellebuyck, who runs a training complex with about three dozen  
runners in Albuquerque, said he realized midway through the race 
that Vigueras was too strong to catch. 
</P>
<P>
	He aimed for either second or third -- ahead of the faltering  
Larson and exploited the downhill on the last course's four miles 
into Point State Park. 
</P>
<P>
	``I turned to Steve and I said, `Let's go get him. We'll both  
make the team,' '' Hellebuyck said. ``I'm a heat runner. I proved 
today that I can run in sunny conditions, and Spain will be even 
hotter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Swift said he has been trying to break 2:20 in the marathon for  
two years but did not expect to finish in the top three and make 
the U.S. team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I put pressure on myself and told myself, `It's got to happen  
soon, or maybe it won't happen at all,' '' he said about the 2:20 
goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Titova, 33, who will next race in San Francisco's marathon, said  
she was buoyed by live bands along the course and estimated that 
she lost five minutes off her time because of temperatures in the 
mid-60s and a lack of cloud cover. 
</P>
<P>
	She said through an interpreter that she ran through spasms in  
her leg muscles during the last three miles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
