<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wohlers Wild in Minor League Outing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) -- Mark Wohlers went back to the mound Sunday  
and his control problems came right back. 
</P>
<P>
	Wohlers had trouble throwing strikes in his debut with the  
Cincinnati Reds' Triple-A team. He walked five of the seven batters 
he faced and threw four wild pitches in one-third of an inning as 
Indianapolis lost to Toledo 8-5 Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Wohlers' first appearance in a game since the Reds got  
him from Atlanta on April 16 for reliever John Hudek. Pitching 
coach Don Gullett has changed a few things in Wohlers' delivery to 
help him regain his control. 
</P>
<P>
	Wohlers, who is on the disabled list with anxiety disorder, came  
in to start the sixth inning with Toledo leading 3-2. He threw 31 
pitches in all, 22 of them balls. 
</P>
<P>
	Wohlers got one strikeout, walked five, gave up one hit, struck  
out one and threw four wild pitches. Afterwards, he declined to be 
interviewed. 
</P>
<P>
	After Hamelin walked to start the inning, Wohlers threw two wild  
pitches with Luis Polonia at bat. Polonia hit an RBI single and 
eventually scored on another wild pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	Ricky Cradle and Jim Bonnici walked before Wohlers got a called  
third strike on Walt McKeel. Walks to Jason Maxwell and Kimera 
Bartee forced in another run and ended Wohlers' outing. 
</P>
<P>
	Wohlers, 29, set an Atlanta Braves record with 39 saves in 1996,  
and had 33 the following season. But last year, he was sent to 
Triple-A Richmond twice when his control deteriorated. 
</P>
<P>
	By the end of the season -- after he pulled a muscle in his side,  
his wife filed for divorce and his mother suffered a heart attack -- 
his confidence was shot. 
</P>
</TEXT>
