<DOCNO> APW19990502.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 10:26:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Marine Jet Crashes in Adriatic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- NATO said Sunday a U.S. Marine Corps  
AV8B Harrier plane crashed in the Adriatic Sea on Saturday while on 
a training mission for operations in the Balkans. The pilot was 
reported safely rescued. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second report of a crashed U.S. warplane in 24 hours  
operating over and around Yugoslavia. Neither pilot's name was 
released. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours earlier, the alliance said a U.S. F-16 fighter plane had  
gone down over western Serbia early Sunday. NATO said the crash was 
caused by engine failure, but Yugoslav authorities claimed the jet 
was shot down. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Aviano air base in Italy, Air Force Capt. Ed  
Thomas, said Sunday the F-16 pilot returned to Aviano ``in really 
good condition and really good spirits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pilot, an American, is expected to quickly return to action.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know the guy. He's a really, really good officer,'' Thomas  
said. ``I'd be surprised at anything less. We're so grateful that 
he's back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``And out of 12,000 sorties,'' Thomas said, ``we haven't lost a  
single pilot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas declined to give details of the rescue operation other  
than to say that both ``fixed wing'' aircraft and helicopters were 
involved. Some of the aircraft were ``probably'' out of Aviano, 
although the base is not the primary one for special operations. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said the AV8B Harrier plane crashed  
into the sea while approaching a carrier of the Marine 
Expeditionary Force to land. 
</P>
<P>
	Shea said the plane was not involved in attacks on Yugoslavia  
when it came down and there was no suspicion it has hit by hostile 
fire. 
</P>
<P>
	The Harrier was assigned to the Marine Attack Squadron 231 from  
Cherry Point, N.C. It is part of the Marine Expeditionary Unit 
deployed in support of the NATO operation in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO has now acknowledged the loss of two other aircraft since  
the air campaign against Yugoslavia began on March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. F-117 stealth fighter went down over Yugoslavia on March  
27. The pilot of that plane was also rescued. An Apache helicopter 
gunship crashed in flames last week on a training mission in 
Albania. Its crewmen escaped with cuts and bruises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
