<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> German Telekom Denies Move Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Deutsche Telekom AG denied on Sunday a  
magazine report that said it planned to move the headquarters of 
its mobile telecommunications unit to Rome if its planned merger 
with Telecom Italia SpA goes ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	Der Spiegel newsmagazine reported in this week's issue that  
Telekom chairman Ron Summer intended to relocate the group's 
T-Mobil unit from Bonn to appease Italian politicians over the 
proposed $82 billion merger plan. 
</P>
<P>
	But a Telekom spokesman denied such relocation plans. He added,  
however, that it was possible that the mobile telecoms division of 
the merged company could be headed by an Italian board member. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti SpA opened a hostile bid for Telecom Italia on Friday,  
and investors are waiting to see whether the Italian government 
will side with Olivetti or back the merger with Deutsche Telekom. 
</P>
<P>
	Italian officials have expressed hope that Telecom Italia, a  
former state-owned monopoly, will remain in Italian hands, and have 
pressed the German government to cut the 72 percent stake it still 
holds in Deutsche Telekom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
