<HEADLINE> Cards' Top Pick Injured in Drill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Wide receiver David Boston, the Arizona  
Cardinals' top draft pick last month, fractured his left shoulder 
blade Sunday during a mini-camp passing drill. 
</P>
<P>
	Team officials said Boston, taken at No. 8 overall out of Ohio  
State, will need up to six weeks to heal but should be ready for 
the start of training camp July 30 in Flagstaff. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston was injured when he caught a long pass from Jake Plummer  
over defensive back Corey Chavous and both fell heavily to the 
turf. X-rays showed a hairline fracture of the shoulder blade. 
</P>
<P>
	``We both went up for the ball,'' Chavous said. ``We got our  
feet tangled up and I came down on his shoulder a little bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boston, his left arm in a sling, refused to talk to reporters in  
the locker room after the final day of the team's three-day 
mini-camp. 
</P>
