<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 10:26:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Freed US POWs Reach Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RAMSTEIN, Germany (AP) -- Three U.S. soldiers held in captivity  
by Yugoslav authorities for more than a month were released and 
left Yugoslavia on Sunday. Holding hands with the Rev. Jesse 
Jackson, they walked into neighboring Croatia chanting ``Free at 
last, free at last, thank God Almighty, free at last!'' 
</P>
<P>
	The soldiers arrived Sunday afternoon at the U.S. military base  
in Ramstein in southwest Germany on a C-9 military plane. 
</P>
<P>
	A color guard with flags and a 27-man honor platoon, dressed in  
full combat gear from the soldiers' own division, greeted them on 
the tarmac at the air base along with a crowd of about 200 
well-wishers holding U.S. flags and big ``Welcome Home'' signs. 
</P>
<P>
	The arrival ended 32 days in captivity for the soldiers, who  
marked their release in the Yugoslav capital of Belgrade on Sunday 
morning with beaming smiles and calls home. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's good to be free,'' exulted Spc. Steven M. Gonzales in the  
Yugoslav capital. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton gave no indication that he was willing to cede  
anything to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic for the gesture. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we welcome our soldiers home, our thoughts also turn to the  
over 1 million Kosovars who are unable to go home because of the 
policies of the regime in Belgrade,'' Clinton said in a White House 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today we reaffirm our resolve to persevere until they, too,  
can return -- with security and self-government,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The three soldiers, carrying American flags folded under their  
arms, walked onto the tarmac in Ramstein, saluted the honor guard, 
then immediately boarded two UH-60 medical evacuation helicopters 
to be flown to the nearby Landstuhl Regional Medical Center, a U.S. 
military hospital where they were to undergo medical evaluations. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson urged the warring sides in the Kosovo conflict to move  
from ``battleground to common ground'' and find a diplomatic 
solution. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you talk, amazing things happen,'' he said. ``Let's seize  
this great moment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two other soldiers were Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez and  
Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone. 
</P>
<P>
	Amid huge smiles and a sense of jubilation in Belgrade, the  
soldiers embraced the U.S. civil rights leader, who said he hoped 
their release would lead to a diplomatic breakthrough in the Kosovo 
conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in Zagreb, Croatia, the soldiers expressed gratitude to  
Jackson and his delegation for mediating their release. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can never thank them enough, we owe them our freedom,''  
Stone said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzales' parents stayed up most of the night, waiting for their  
son's release. Finally Rosie and Gilbert Gonzales received the 
phone call they'd been waiting for. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said, `I love you, Mom and Dad. I'm free. I'll see you  
soon,''' Mrs. Gonzales said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson had called Saturday for NATO to reciprocate Milosevic's  
gesture of releasing the soldiers by calling a pause in its bombing 
campaign. But strikes went on through the night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that the NATO alliance will see this for what it is  
worth and not be cynical about that possibility, because the 
alternative to diplomacy would be a war with no end in sight,'' 
Jackson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The soldiers' release could be a sign Milosevic is moving to  
find a way to end the Kosovo crisis. The Yugoslav leader might also 
be trying to improve his image in the United States and to exploit 
anti-war rumblings in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president took the decision in support of Jesse Jackson's  
peace efforts,'' Tanjug said. ``We do not see them as enemies but 
victims of war and militarism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials were cautious in their initial responses to the  
announced release. 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said the release of the  
prisoners would have no effect on NATO's air campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Bacon also said it was premature to talk about a reciprocal  
release of Yugoslav prisoners. The United States captured one 
prisoner two weeks ago, and Bacon said NATO is now holding a 
second. He released no details on the second capture, except to say 
it was ``very recently,'' apparently within the last 24 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon officials had previously all but ruled out a prisoner  
exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson made several pleas Saturday for NATO to halt its  
airstrikes, saying ``in the coming days, we shall urge all parties 
to seize upon this initiative'' and undertake new negotiations to 
end the crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Stone, 25, was from Smiths Creek, Michigan; Gonzales, 22, from  
Huntsville, Texas; and Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	During their meeting Saturday, Jackson said Milosevic addressed  
the four points raised by the United States and NATO: halting the 
violence in Kosovo, allowing the return of refugees, the presence 
of a multinational force and a political solution to the crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	``But he is going to send to President Clinton a letter laying  
out his response to those four basic concerns, the desire to meet 
with him and to take this matter to resolution through 
negotiations,'' Jackson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of Jackson's religious delegation said that during the  
meeting Jackson prayed with Milosevic and held his hand. Then, the 
whole American and Yugoslav delegation held hands and bowed their 
heads in prayer. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson had met with the three soldiers Friday in Belgrade, and  
the three told him of being held in isolation. The Friday meeting 
with Jackson was the first time the three had seen each other since 
their capture. They appeared generally healthy, but still showed 
cuts and bruises they suffered when captured. 
</P>
<P>
	The alliance launched the air campaign to force Milosevic to  
accept a Western-dictated peace deal for Kosovo, including 
widespread autonomy for the province and 28,000 NATO troops to 
enforce it. 
</P>
<P>
	Ethnic Albanians comprised about 90 percent of Kosovo's prewar  
population of 2 million people. More than 600,000 of them have fled 
Kosovo and Serb forces since the alliance's air campaign began. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990502.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 13:32:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers Accused of Cuba Recruiting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Two Cuban minor leaguers say the Los Angeles  
Dodgers held secret tryouts for them in their homeland, arranged 
their escapes and then ordered them to lie about it, according to 
The Boston Globe. 
</P>
<P>
	First baseman Juan Carlos Diaz, 23, and outfielder Josue Perez,  
21, have asked the commissioner's office to declare them free 
agents on grounds they were signed illegally. 
</P>
<P>
	If true, the Dodgers' actions would violate baseball rules  
prohibiting scouting in Cuba. They also may violate the U.S. trade 
embargo against the communist nation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I understand that nobody should go to Cuba,'' Dodgers senior  
vice president Ralph Avila told the Globe. ``Look, I don't work for 
the immigration. I don't work for the State Department. I don't 
work for the police department. If someone went to Cuba, it's not 
my business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pablo Peguero, the scout accused of arranging the defections,  
said he hasn't been to Cuba in more than 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Diaz said Peguero approached him in 1995 after a game in Havana  
and offered a tryout for the next morning. Afterward, Diaz said, 
Peguero told him the Dodgers wanted to bring him to the Dominican 
Republic. Two months later, Peguero returned with a woman he said 
was his cousin. 
</P>
<P>
	Diaz received a visa after the woman told authorities his family  
helped her find a Cuban doctor for surgery she needed. She said she 
had invited Diaz to the Dominican Republic to show her gratitude 
and paid all his expenses, Diaz said. 
</P>
<P>
	Diaz went to the Dodgers' training academy at Campo Las Palmas  
outside Santo Domingo, where Avila signed him to a contract with a 
$65,000 bonus. Last year, Diaz hit a combined 30 homers at Single-A 
and Double-A. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if they paid off people or what, but I  
immediately got my provisional residency papers, which enabled me 
to sign,'' Diaz said, adding that Peguero and Avila told him to lie 
if asked how he escaped to the Dominican Republic. 
</P>
<P>
	Perez, who plays for the Dodgers' Single-A team at Vero Beach,  
Fla., told a similar story in a separate interview. He said after a 
1996 tryout with Peguero he was escorted to the Dominican Republic 
by a young woman he never saw again. Perez was signed to a contract 
with a $40,000 bonus, and also was told to lie about his escape, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The players said they came forward after realizing their signing  
bonuses were low. 
</P>
<P>
	The commissioner's office has said teams breaking rules against  
scouting in Cuba face fines, suspensions or loss of amateur draft 
choices. 
</P>
<P>
	In the only documented case of scouting in Cuba, Miami-based  
agent Juan Ignacio Hernandez was arrested for trying to persuade 
players to defect. Hernandez was sentenced to 15 years in prison by 
Cuban authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Dodgers did recruit players from Cuba, they could be in  
violation of the 36-year trade embargo prohibiting American 
companies from conducting business on the island. Individuals can 
be fined up to $55,000 for violations, and corporations up to 
$250,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
