<HEADLINE> Golfer Elkington Has Meningitis  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	THE WOODLANDS, Texas (AP) -- Steve Elkington was being treated  
Sunday for viral meningitis, an illness that sidelined the PGA Tour 
player for a time last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Elkington, a 36-year-old Australian who attended the University  
of Houston and lives in Houston, withdrew Sunday from the Shell 
Houston Open. He went to a Houston hospital Saturday night 
complaining of severe headaches and spent the night. He remained 
there Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Steve contracted viral meningitis again like he did last  
year,'' Brian Peters, a spokesman for International Management 
Group, Elkington's agent, told Houston television station KRIV 
Sunday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not life-threatening but he is in a lot of pain. We  
expect him to be out of the hospital in a few days and back on the 
tour in a few weeks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elkington was five strokes behind leader Hal Sutton entering the  
final round. Stuart Appleby won the tournament by one stroke over 
Sutton and John Cook. 
</P>
<P>
	Elkington spent most of 1998 fighting health problems, including  
meningitis that was diagnosed just before last year's Byron Nelson 
Classic. He bounced back to win the Buick Challenge in October. 
</P>
<P>
	Elkington picked up his 10th career win in March at the Doral  
Ryder Open and is 12th on the PGA money list this year with 
$776,263. His career victories include two titles at the Players 
Championships and the 1995 PGA Championship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
