<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Murdered Grandmother Remembered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- John Rizzotti was age 8 when his  
great-grandmother died. He was 10 when he found out how. 
</P>
<P>
	That was when he stumbled across a box of horrors -- news  
clippings, autopsy reports, pictures -- that laid out the last 
terrifying moments of life for 78-year-old Leah Schendel, stripped 
from the chest down and battered with punches that broke her 
dentures and stopped her frail heart. 
</P>
<P>
	Sixteen years later, the pain hasn't gone away.  
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Mrs. Schendel's killer, Manuel Babbitt, is scheduled  
to pay for that crime with his life. Only then, Rizzotti thinks, 
will he start to get over his great-grandmother's death. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want him to feel the exact same fear that she felt when he  
threw himself through her door,'' he says. ``I want him to feel 
that pain that we had when we had no grandmother for Christmas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Babbitt's supporters, who argue he was in the grip of a Vietnam  
flashback when he killed, say Rizzotti's feelings are 
understandable but mistaken. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will be no closure here because hate doesn't die,'' says  
defense lawyer Chuck Patterson. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The last night of Leah Schendel's life started well.  
</P>
<P>
	Her brother, Aaron Weinberg, and his wife had come to Sacramento  
and taken her to a sister's house for dinner. Later, they brought 
her back to her garden apartment in a senior citizens' complex, 
carefully walking her to the door. 
</P>
<P>
	As she often did, Mrs. Schendel locked her screen door and left  
the inside one open for air. Judging by how the apartment was later 
found, she dealt a hand of solitaire, a game she loved to play, and 
turned the TV to a channel showing war movies. 
</P>
<P>
	The next morning, Dec. 19, 1980, the landlady found her  
half-naked body under a mattress. 
</P>
<P>
	Laura Thompson, Mrs. Schendel's granddaughter, recalls trying to  
clean up her grandmother's ransacked apartment and watching her 
mother find a pillow soaked in blood. ``I'll never forget that 
scream.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Smiling out from family photos, Mrs. Schendel is the  
silver-haired picture of grandmotherhood. 
</P>
<P>
	The family called her ``Gramma.'' They remember how she used to  
pass out silver dollars from her occasional trips to Reno -- ``I 
don't think she ever went bigger than the nickel machines,'' Ms. 
Thompson says with a laugh -- and how she loved being around her 
grandchildren and great-grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Thompson doesn't remember her grandmother talking much about  
her own past, her childhood as a turn-of-the-century Jewish 
immigrant, what happened to other branches of the family -- ``You 
could never talk to her about the Holocaust.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She does remember her grandmother being firmly fixed in the  
present, making afghans, taking a class to learn to make 
professional-looking ceramics, cooking batches of latkes -- potato 
pancakes -- for Hanukah. 
</P>
<P>
	She never had a driver's license, but that didn't stop her from  
getting around. Ms. Thompson recalls how her just-under-5-foot, 
100-pound grandmother would drag a shopping cart back and forth to 
the local supermarket to get groceries under her own steam. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was a very independent lady,'' she says.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Babbitt has family, too.  
</P>
<P>
	His brother, Bill, who turned Babbitt in to police, made a  
moving plea at a hearing in April as he asked Gov. Gray Davis to 
show mercy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm up here shaking like a leaf because as I'm running out of  
patience for justice. My brother Manny's running out of ... time,'' 
he said. ``I don't want Manny's blood on my hands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Davis rejected Babbitt's clemency bid. Defense  
attorneys are making a last attempt to stay the execution with an 
appeal asking the state Supreme Court to throw out Babbitt's 
conviction and order a new trial on the grounds that attorney 
misconduct made his original defense flawed. 
</P>
<P>
	Defenders say Babbitt, who received a Purple Heart for his  
service in the 77-day siege of Khe Sanh, one of the bloodiest 
battles of the Vietnam war, was suffering post-traumatic stress 
disorder when he murdered Mrs. Schendel and was not in his right 
mind. 
</P>
<P>
	They also argue that his trial lawyer did a terrible job of  
defending him in 1982 and they question whether Babbitt, who is 
black, got impartial treatment from the all-white jury. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those trying to get Babbitt's life spared were a Florida  
prosecutor, scores of Khe Sanh veterans and David Kaczynski -- who 
like Bill Babbitt, tipped police to the wrongdoing of a brother, in 
his case Unabomber Theodore Kaczynski. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Thompson understands why the Babbitts fight for life. ``My  
heart goes out to the Babbitts. I would never want to be in their 
shoes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But she hopes they lose.  
</P>
<P>
	``We want justice to be done,'' she says. ``The only way you can  
get justice is to have the death penalty and to have the execution 
carried out to show people you just can't go out there and kill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rizzotti, Ms. Thompson's nephew, hopes to see Babbitt die.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to say that about another person's life. We don't  
like the fact that another person is dying in this case, but ... 
there's no way around it,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	``What he did destroyed an entire family.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
