<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Couple Cultivates 2 Million Worms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REA, Pa. (AP) -- A few times each day, Kay Ihnat grabs a  
paintbrush, scrapes away the top layer of dirt from a pile and 
uncovers what looks like a handful of fettucini in red sauce. 
</P>
<P>
	Fettucini that moves, that is.  
</P>
<P>
	Ihnat and her husband, John, keep 2 million redworms in wooden  
boxes and pickup truck beds in an old dairy barn near the small 
southwestern Pennsylvania village of Rea. 
</P>
<P>
	The redworms -- Lumbricus rubellus to scientists -- are shipped  
across the country for bait at $10 to $18 a pound and in worm 
recycling boxes that sell for $35 to $2,289.50. The biggest kits 
are for schools, where worms are a fun science project. 
</P>
<P>
	``Worm farming is the kind of thing you can do in your  
backyard,'' Jayson Harper, a farm economics professor at Penn State 
University, said Wednesday. ``It's very low-tech -- something even a 
kid could do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The kid would have to work pretty hard, however.  
</P>
<P>
	It takes about 45 minutes just to get a few pounds of worms out  
of a shovelful of dirt on a plywood production line. A bright light 
the worms dislike is aimed at the pile, forcing them down slowly. 
The top layer of dirt is then swept off, and the process starts 
over. 
</P>
<P>
	The farm requires so much labor -- from hauling manure and rotten  
lettuce for worm food to bagging soil enriched with worm waste for 
potting soil -- that none of the Ihnats' six children is interested 
in taking over. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's driving us crazy,'' Kay Ihnat said. ``You'll see an ad  
in the newspaper a few years from now when we are old and gray -- 
`Worm farm for sale.''' 
</P>
<P>
	It could be a good investment. The Ihnats are about to add their  
fourth roomful of worm-raising beds to complement the 42 beds they 
have now. Kay Ihnat said she is thinking about getting a chair 
instead of a couch for their den so she can have more room to store 
outgoing worms and worm kits. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest challenge in running a worm farm is marketing, John  
Ihnat said. The growth area for the worm business is recycling 
boxes. They come in designer colors and can sit beneath someone's 
sink. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecology is the big selling point. Not surprisingly, worm boxes  
are more popular in California. Harper, the Penn State farming 
professor, said some small towns have even tried worm recycling for 
leaves and grass clippings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Half of the people just don't want worms in their house, and  
there is nothing you can say to them,'' said Kay Ihnat, who speaks 
at schools as the ``Worm Lady.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The other half you try to appeal to,'' she said. ``Think of  
all the biodegradable waste that's sitting out there in landfills, 
in non-biodegradable bags. And if you run the garbage disposal, 
that takes an average of eight gallons of water a day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What's yummy for the family dog -- meats and cheeses -- are bad  
for worms. So are oranges, but not grapefruit, strangely enough. 
Everything else that will decompose in nature is good -- including 
newspaper, eggshells and coffee grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ihnats took up worm farming after getting married six years  
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The pitfalls were many, including the fact that worms kept dying  
on delivery trucks. A switch to the U.S. Postal Service, which has 
climate control in the back of its vehicles, saved the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Kay Ihnat, a former lab manager at a cancer clinic, had tried  
and failed at a wallpaper business. John Ihnat was tired of chasing 
dairy cows around the weeping willows on the family homestead and 
had investigated emu, ostrich and rabbit farming as well as hops 
fields for beer. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple decided on worm farming after getting married, just  
three months after Kay Ihnat met her husband at a bachelor auction. 
The Ihnats have six daughters from previous marriages. 
</P>
<P>
	The thrifty couple later plucked a cement mixer from a garbage  
dump to use for mixing dirt, got a great deal on equipment from a 
worm farm that went bust, and fought off moles and three especially 
pesky raccoons. 
</P>
<P>
	The good thing is that worms breed fast, so fast they make  
rabbits look celibate. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just phenomenal. I tried to figure out the math on it  
once, and I had to give up. They sit down there in the dark all 
day, so they have nothing else to do,'' Kay Ihnat said. 
</P>
<P>
	 *End advance for Monday, May 3    	
</P>
<P>
 *BC-EXP--Worms-Facts, adv03,0194    	
</P>
<P>
 *$adv03    	
</P>
<P>
 *For release Monday, May 3, and thereafter    	
</P>
<P>
 *Some facts about worms    	
</P>
<P>
 *With BC-EXP--Worms Aplenty    	
</P>
<P>
                       *By The Associated Press    	
</P>
<P>
	Some facts about worms and worm farming:  
</P>
<P>
	-- A pound of redworms will eat a pound of garbage in two days.  
Feeding the worms too much attracts mites, which compete with the 
worms for food. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Worm farmers prefer redworms to nightcrawlers because they are  
easier to raise, but nightcrawlers are generally considered to be 
better bait. 
</P>
<P>
	-- A mature redworm grows a band around the middle. If faced with  
a shortage of food, ``the older ones will quit eating and die just 
so the little ones can eat,'' worm farmer Kay Ihnat said. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Building and stocking a wooden worm bed that produces 168  
pounds of worms per year costs about $300. Three hours a week are 
needed to harvest a bed of that size. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Worm waste, also called castings, contains calcium, magnesium,  
nitrogen and phosphates and potash that can help plants grow. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	Sources: Worm farmers John and Kay Ihnat and Penn State farm  
economics professor Jayson Harper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
