<HEADLINE> Mrs. Gore Addresses School Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tipper Gore says parents and other adults  
should take greater care with children's mental health after the 
Littleton, Colo. school shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we are serious about stopping the violence and helping our  
children, we as adults need to erase the stigma that prevents our 
kids from getting the help they need for their mental health,'' 
Mrs. Gore, the wife of Vice President Al Gore, said in an essay 
written for this week's edition of Time magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we know a child is depressed or alienated, we need to take  
emergency action and stay involved with the problem,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	An advocate for mental health issues, Mrs. Gore said, ``The  
alarm that sounded in Littleton should wake up all Americans to the 
special needs of our children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The toxic culture of guns and screen violence that kids have  
to navigate has been created by adults who are supposed to offer 
protection and guidance,'' she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
