<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Race Deaths Raise Safety Questions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- For the second time in nine months a crash  
at a major open-wheel auto race in the United States has killed 
three spectators, raising questions about safety at the events. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every once in a while, unfortunately, auto racing raises the  
black side of itself,'' Lowe's Motor Speedway president H.A. 
``Humpy'' Wheeler said Sunday as authorities tried to piece 
together evidence from a fatal accident at the track Saturday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	Three people were killed and eight hurt, including a 9-year-old  
girl who was critically injured, when debris from a three-car wreck 
flew into the stands during the VisionAire 500 Pep Boys Indy Racing 
League event. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses said the force of the crash at speeds near 215 mph  
rocketed a wheel and suspension parts over a 15-foot-high catch 
fence at the exit of the fourth turn. The debris flew into the 
grandstands and slammed into spectators, some of them seated 
several dozen rows above the 1.5-mile, high-banked superspeedway. 
</P>
<P>
	As shrieking spectators sought help, rescue workers converged on  
the bloody area in a scenario eerily similar to that at Michigan 
Speedway last July 26, when three spectators were killed in a Champ 
Car race. The cause in that event also was a broken wheel and 
suspension parts that hurdled a catch fence. 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort to keep wheels from flying off at impact, the  
Formula One circuit this year began requiring its teams to use 
tethers designed to keep the wheels and suspension connected to the 
main body of the machine. 
</P>
<P>
	Such tethers are not required on either Champ Cars or IRL  
machines, in part because some racing authorities think the devices 
may solve one problem while creating another. 
</P>
<P>
	Leo Mehl, executive director of the IRL, said there is concern  
that while tethers may prevent parts from flying off cars and 
hitting fans, they also may put drivers in greater danger because 
the parts could snap back and hit them instead. A tethered wheel 
also could be especially dangerous if it is launched into the 
stands in a slingshot fashion, Mehl said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have spent a lot of time looking at that regulation and  
discussing it,'' Mehl said, adding that the IRL feels the matter 
needs more study. ``You must be very cautious that you don't make 
regulations that will make things worse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mehl said the IRL would work with the suburban Charlotte track  
to determine if anything can be done to prevent a recurrence. The 
height of Charlotte's catch fence conforms to industry standards, 
but it was difficult to tell how much higher the fence would have 
had to be to keep the debris from reaching the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have very little direct film of the accident,'' Mehl said.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheeler said the IRL and the speedway planned their own  
investigations to augment the efforts of their insurers, ``to make 
sure that this never happens again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The three people killed were Randy D. Pyatte, 21, and Jeff  
Patton, no age available, both of Connelly Springs, and Dexter B. 
Mobley, 41, of Statesville. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven of the eight people hospitalized were released by Sunday  
evening. The lone exception was Hailey McGee, 9, of Conover, who 
was in critical condition at Carolinas Medical Center in Charlotte 
with bruises to her brain and lungs. 
</P>
<P>
	The fatalities were the first involving spectators for both the  
IRL, which was founded in 1996, and the speedway, which opened in 
1960. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheeler, who has long been known as one of the sport's most  
outgoing promoters and an innovator in creative pre-race shows, 
remained visibly shaken Sunday afternoon, about 18 hours after the 
crash. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've talked to a lot of people who have been through it, but I  
certainly understand it a lot better now,'' said Wheeler, who went 
to the grandstand after the crash and tried to comfort some of the 
victims. 
</P>
<P>
	The speedway canceled the race shortly after the accident and  
said it would refund the ticket prices for the approximately 50,000 
spectators. Shortly after the announcement was made, however, some 
people began calling the speedway's switchboard to say the track 
could earmark their refunds for a trust fund for the victims. 
Speedway officials said they planned to have a trust account opened 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident occurred in the last race of a three-year  
sanctioning agreement between the IRL and the speedway, prompting 
questions about whether the track might not seek to renew its 
agreement with the circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Further clouding the issue is the fact that the Charlotte track  
is owned by Speedway Motorsports Inc., which controls tracks that 
hold five of the 11 races on this year's IRL schedule. Should the 
IRL lose the support of SMI, it could spell serious trouble for the 
fledgling circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	But Wheeler, who in addition to running the Charlotte track also  
serves as SMI's president, said the company remains committed to 
helping the IRL establish itself as a low-cost alternative to the 
Champ Car circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have pretty strong feelings about the IRL,'' he said.  
``They're trying to do the right thing.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
