<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 18:31:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buffett Criticizes High-Fee Brokers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Multibillionaire investor Warren Buffett on  
Sunday criticized for stockbrokers and investment managers who take 
high fees for their work. 
</P>
<P>
	Investment managers add nothing to the value of the businesses  
they trade stocks in, yet many demand 2 percent and 3 percent 
commissions and fees to help their clients invest, Buffett said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The average investment manager adds nothing,'' Buffett said.  
``He subtracts something from your investment performance. It's 
almost unique among professions that I can think of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Known for investing in companies he likes and holding the stock  
indefinitely, Buffett's estimated wealth of more than $29 billion 
makes him the second richest man in America behind Microsoft Corp. 
chairman Bill Gates, who has $58 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffett's holding company, Berkshire Hathaway Inc., invests in  
or owns businesses such as General Re and Geico insurance 
companies, Coca-Cola, Nebraska Furniture Mart, The Washington Post, 
International Dairy Queen and See's Candies. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference Sunday during Berkshire Hathaway's annual  
stockholders meeting, Buffett said people who want to invest in the 
stock market should learn about a business, trust its management 
and project earnings into the future. Then, he said, they should 
buy the stock and hold it. 
</P>
<P>
	People investing in mutual funds should make certain the fees  
charged are not too high, Buffett said, and give up hope that their 
investment will do anything better than average. 
</P>
<P>
	Another option is forming a pool of fellow investors who want to  
buy interests in the same companies, Buffett suggested. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, Buffett also has criticized trading stocks in the  
same day for incremental gains, known as ``day-trading.'' saying 
the cost in commissions often outweigh any small gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffett's words are weighed heavily by many of his stockholders,  
about 15,000 of whom were expected at the three-day stockholders' 
extravaganza. 
</P>
<P>
	Many stockholders are with the company for life, and the price  
per share reflects that. Class A stock closed Friday at $76,400 a 
share, Class B stock at $2,470 a share. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
