<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mets Celebrate 1969 Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Mets were not willing to compare  
World Series championships Sunday as they celebrated the 30th 
anniversary of their first title. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't play that game of one era is '69 and another era is  
'86,'' said Bud Harrelson, who played for the 1969 team and coached 
the 1986 club. ``They were both great teams. The difference is that 
the '86 Mets went from wire to wire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harrelson, a scrappy, light-hitting shortstop, was an integral  
part of the '69 World Series champs, who defeated the seemingly 
unbeatable Baltimore Orioles in five games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We weren't expected to win, which made it phenomenal and  
special,'' Harrelson said before the Mets' old-timers beat a team 
of former big league stars 7-0. ``We were America's team. We were 
loved by everybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harrelson coached third base for the 1986 champions, who coasted  
to a franchise-best 108 wins, but had to struggle through a 
pressure-packed NL championship series against Houston and an even 
more dramatic World Series against Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Current Mets bench coach Bruce Benedict was in the dugout during  
the old-timers' game and listened to ex-Mets tell stories about the 
'69 season. 
</P>
<P>
	``They weren't expected to win, but they were a wonderful  
defensive team,'' Benedict said. ``They had outstanding pitching 
and they got hot at the right time. They got hot at the end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Benedict, a catcher for the Atlanta Braves in 1986, remembered  
the '86 Mets as a talented, close-knit group. 
</P>
<P>
	``They did things for you on an everyday basis,'' Benedict said.  
``You have to have a little luck involved too. I think a lot of 
things have to fall together for you. I think the Mets had all 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mets closer John Franco, honored Saturday for becoming the  
second player to save 400 games, was impressed with the ability of 
the '69 Mets to beat an Orioles team that included future Hall of 
Famers Brooks Robinson, Frank Robinson and Jim Palmer. And this 
after a ninth-place finish in 1968 that matched the Mets' best. 
</P>
<P>
	``They won the whole thing,'' Franco said. ``Nobody expected  
them to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Franco was the Cincinnati Reds' closer in 1986 and faced a  
feared New York lineup which included Keith Hernandez, Gary Carter 
and Darryl Strawberry. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were true professionals. They did the little things to  
win ballgames, got runners over and had a solid lineup. They were 
just a tough team to pitch to.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
