<HEADLINE> Golfer Elkington Hospitalized  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	THE WOODLANDS, Texas (AP) -- Golfer Steve Elkington, in  
contention for a victory Sunday at the Houston Open, had to 
withdraw from the tournament and required hospitalization after 
suffering severe migraines, PGA officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Elkington, 36, an Australian who attended the University of  
Houston and now lives in Houston, sought treatment late Saturday 
and remained in the hospital overnight, forcing him to pull out of 
the event, PGA spokesman Lee Patterson said. 
</P>
<P>
	He was only five strokes behind tournament leader Hal Sutton  
heading into Sunday's fourth and final round. 
</P>
<P>
	Elkington picked up his 10th career win in March at the Doral  
Ryder Open and is 12th on the PGA money list this year with 
$776,263 in winnings. His career victories also include a pair of 
Players Championships and the 1995 PGA Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	He spent most of 1998 fighting health problems, including a bout  
with meningitis, but bounced back to win the Buick Challenge in 
October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
