<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990502.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 22:51:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Willey Credibility Key for Starr </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- A courtroom appearance by Susan McDougal.  
Serious problems with Kathleen Willey's credibility. 
</P>
<P>
	Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's prosecutors may get more to  
handle than they expected in the trial of Julie Hiatt Steele. She 
is accused of obstructing Starr's investigation into Mrs. Willey's 
allegation that President Clinton made an unwanted sexual advance 
toward her. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr is coming off a stinging courtroom setback against Mrs.  
McDougal. So who planned to be on hand for jury selection today? 
</P>
<P>
	``Susan will be there front row center ... in support of  
Julie,'' said Mark Geragos, Mrs. McDougal's lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton has made clear he will not  
allow Ms. Steele's lawyers to put Starr's tactics on trial, as 
happened when Ms. Steele testified in support of Mrs. McDougal, a 
former Whitewater investment partner of Clinton and his wife, 
Hillary. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele's lawyer, Nancy Luque, argued before Hilton that  
Starr's prosecutors made a series of misrepresentations, 
designating Ms. Steele as a mere witness in the investigation when 
they actually regarded her as a major focus of the probe. Ms. 
Steele was tricked into making statements for which she was later 
indicted, her legal team contends. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nancy Luque told me that if she sees an opening to put Starr  
on trial, she'll call Starr as her first witness and Susan McDougal 
right behind him,'' said Geragos. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense has subpoenaed testimony and notes from Newsweek  
magazine reporter Michael Isikoff, who first wrote about Mrs. 
Willey's allegation. The defense team also issued a subpoena to CBS 
for outtakes from a ``60 Minutes'' interview with Mrs. Willey. 
</P>
<P>
	Hilton has yet to decide whether to allow that evidence into the  
case. CBS and Newsweek are seeking to quash the subpoenas. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Willey says she confided Clinton's alleged sexual advance  
to Ms. Steele, a fellow resident of the Richmond, Va., area, the 
day it occurred in 1993. Ms. Steele initially supported Mrs. 
Willey's version of events to Newsweek, then recanted, telling her 
revised account to the FBI and two grand juries. 
</P>
<P>
	She now says the first time she heard the allegation was when  
Mrs. Willey called her in 1997 and asked her to back up her story 
to Isikoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's office has not said whether Mrs. Willey will testify,  
but Ms. Steele's lawyers are assuming that she will and are 
marshaling evidence about Mrs. Willey's background that they hope 
to use to destroy her credibility. 
</P>
<P>
	Steele lawyer Dan Marino referred to some of that evidence  
Friday, noting that one witness interviewed by Starr's office had 
``extremely bad things to say about Mrs. Willey's credibility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another witness, said Marino, alleged that Mrs. Willey ``asked  
her to lie.'' He complained that Starr's office has been slow to 
turn over evidence calling Mrs. Willey's credibility into question. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's office denies that and says the information from such  
witnesses has nothing to do with Mrs. Willey's accusation against 
Clinton. It says it has witnesses besides Mrs. Willey who will 
testify that Ms. Steele knew of the alleged sexual advance well 
before 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Willey aired her allegation in a national television  
interview 14 months ago, triggering a furious counterattack by the 
president's supporters. Clinton denied her story under oath. 
</P>
<P>
	In a risky move for a criminal defendant about to go on trial,  
Ms. Steele took the witness stand in the McDougal case and depicted 
herself as a struggling single parent who was a victim of a 
vengeful Starr. A juror in the McDougal trial in Little Rock, Ark., 
said later he found Ms. Steele's testimony compelling and that it 
gave added credibility to Mrs. McDougal's story that she feared 
Starr's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors acquitted Mrs. McDougal of a charge she obstructed  
Starr's investigation and deadlocked on two counts of criminal 
contempt for refusing to testify before a grand jury. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990502.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 11:22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Star Wars: May the Toys Be With You </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
