<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Landless workers in Brazil are  
escalating their campaign of seizing land in their push for 
agrarian reform, a magazine reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Landless Workers Movement, known as the MST, invaded 244  
sites in the first four months of 1999, a 40 percent jump over the 
same period last year, Veja magazine reported. One-third were 
working ranches, Veja said. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics say the MST, in trying to court publicity, destroys the  
ranches it grabs, sometimes wrecking machinery or killing animals. 
</P>
<P>
	The MST, which has thousands of members in poor northeastern  
states, was founded in 1984 to urge land reforms in Brazil, where 
88 percent of arable land is owned by 20 percent of the population. 
The poorest 40 percent owns just 1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) -- Seven of nine young convicts  
who escaped from a youth prison have been recaptured, police said 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	But the most dangerous of the escapees, Gustavo Adolfo Paredes,  
remained at large. Paredes, 17, was serving a seven year sentence 
for killing at least 20 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine escaped early Friday from a makeshift youth prison in  
San Francisco Gotera, northeast of the capital. The prison, a 
converted military barracks, held 200 prisoners who had been 
transferred from another prison that is being remodeled. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) -- Nicaragua gains its fourth daily  
newspaper this week, a new 16-page paper called La Noticia that is 
due to appear on the stands in the capital Monday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be a very modern newspaper in full color,'' said its  
director, Horacio Ruiz. The initial press run will be 7,000 copies. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruiz, who long worked for the local daily La Prensa, said the  
paper at first will circulate only in the area of the capital while 
it acquires and installs its own press. The initial editions will 
be printed by another newspaper, El Nuevo Diario. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruiz said the newspaper will be independent, denying widespread  
rumors that it is linked to the governing Constitutionalist Liberal 
Party. 
</P>
