<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Citadel To Graduate Woman Cadet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- The bitter fight over admitting women to  
The Citadel now long past, Nancy Mace is about to become the 
156-year-old South Carolina state military school's first female 
cadet to graduate. 
</P>
<P>
	Mace, who entered in the fall of 1996 after the college dropped  
its all-male admissions policy, is to receive her degree with about 
400 male cadets at commencement ceremonies on Saturday. The 
business major transferred credits from a community college to 
graduate a year early. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's done it all on her own with no help from daddy,'' said  
her father, retired Army Brig. Gen. J. Emory Mace, who became the 
school's commandant of cadets during his daughter's first year 
there. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would make an effort not to associate with her,'' he said.  
``You need to make it on your own and blend in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mace, 21, who is taking an analyst job with a business  
consulting firm in Charlotte, N.C., leaves the Citadel with a 
mixture of pride and humility. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still don't think of it in an historic context,'' she said  
in Sunday's The (Charleston) Post and Courier. ``I just wanted an 
opportunity to join the long, gray line. I think I am paving the 
way for other women ... but I don't think of myself as a pioneer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Citadel now has 42 female cadets, a number expected to  
increase to about 90 next year, said Bonnie Jo Houchen, who 
graduated with the first women at the U.S. Air Force Academy and 
now serves as The Citadel's assistant commandant helping oversee 
the assimilation of women. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to give everyone time to accept the reality,''  
Houchen said. ``Some men in the corps still don't like women 
here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shannon Faulkner sued over the all-male admissions policy and  
became the first woman cadet under a federal court order in 1995, 
but she dropped out after less than a week, citing the loneliness 
and stress. 
</P>
<P>
	The legal fight continued with other women while the state and  
Citadel supporters contended that all-male schools promoted 
diversity in education. Before the case could reach the U.S. 
Supreme Court, however, the justices ruled that Virginia Military 
Institute's all-male policy was unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	Faced with that decision, Citadel officials decided to open the  
school's gates to women. Two women will graduate from VMI this year 
as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Mace entered The Citadel in 1996 with four other women, two of  
whom left after a semester, saying they had been hazed and 
harassed. The fourth was Petra Lovetinska, who will oversee 
military training for freshmen athletes this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``In my company, guys will tell me, 'I didn't like women coming  
here and I still don't like women here but I respect what you do 
and I respect you,' '' said Lovetinska. ``Some of my biggest 
supporters did fight the fight and they didn't want women at The 
Citadel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Regimental Commander Reed Wilson, the school's highest-ranking  
cadet, said women will be more accepted with each passing year. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you see the class of '99 leave you will see a change in  
the air here,'' Wilson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mace told the Charleston newspaper her graduation has more  
meaning because of the hardships she endured. 
</P>
<P>
	``Separating your emotions all the time is very tiring and I  
have broken down in tears,'' she said. ``But I have never said I 
wanted to quit.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990502.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 11:51:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Struggles in World Hockey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAMAR, Norway (AP) -- Winner of 23 world titles and eight Olympic  
gold medals as the Soviet Union, Russia appears a weaker team at 
hockey's world championships. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians struggled to a 2-2 tie Sunday against Belarus,  
which is making only its second appearance in this tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Ottawa Senators captain Alexei Yashin, the only NHL player on  
the Russian team, scored the opening goal in the Group D game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's right to say we're disappointed,'' Yashin  
said. ``It was only our first game and our team was nervous at the 
start. I'm sure we'll get better as we go along.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sergei Tertyshny saved Russia from a loss by scoring the tying  
goal. 
</P>
<P>
	In a Group B opener in Oslo, Switzerland rallied to beat Latvia  
5-3. The United States opened play in Group C on Saturday by 
routing Japan 7-1. The Americans play Austria in Oslo on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Belarus-Russia game, Yashin showed no lingering effects  
from a fever, scoring short-handed 4:19 into the game. Oleg Romanov 
answered for Belarus 1:15 later with a wrist shot from the blue 
line. 
</P>
<P>
	At 11:04 into the second, Aleksandr Andrievsky put Belarus  
ahead, swiping in a rebound. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians averted an upset by the former Soviet republic when  
Tertyshny flipped the puck above goalie Andrei Mezin's right glove 
from the top of the slot at 5:02 in the third. 
</P>
<P>
	``The team was nervous in the first period but they played well  
in the other two,'' Yashin said. ``Belarus played a good game and 
they didn't give us many opportunities. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, there was the danger we might lose at one point,  
but if you are afraid of losing, chances are you will.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Oslo, Marcel Jenni led the way for the Swiss, last year's  
surprising semifinalist. He broke a 3-3 tie at 18:39 in the second 
period and added the go-ahead goal at 13:44 in the third period. 
</P>
<P>
	On his last goal, he stole the puck from a Latvian near the blue  
line, skated in and beat goalie Andrejs Zinkovs to the stick side. 
</P>
<P>
	Mathias Seger, Mark Streit and Mattia Baldi had the other Swiss  
goals. Aleksandrs Semjonovs, Aleksandrs Kercs and Andrejs Maticins 
scored for Latvia. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a young team and they were nervous early,'' Swiss  
coach Ralph Krueger said. ``But they played really well in the 
third period and we also had excellent goaltending.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990502.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 23:32:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Conn. School Honors Dylan McDermott </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WATERBURY, Conn. (AP) -- Dylan McDermott was late to school. But  
he didn't get in trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	The actor, who plays lawyer Bobby Donnell on ABC's ``The  
Practice,'' was scheduled to attend a fund-raiser Saturday at his 
old grade school, St. Mary's School, and receive a Distinguished 
Alumnus Award. 
</P>
<P>
	His flight from St. Louis was canceled, so the ceremony was  
pushed back nearly two hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm filled with so many different emotions coming back to  
Waterbury,'' McDermott said when he finally arrived. ``I'm here 
being honored, but I think we should be honoring St. Mary's. The 
school gave me so much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McDermott, dressed in a charcoal designer suit with matching  
shirt and tie, took some ribbing about looking like his character 
on ``The Practice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm always in a suit,'' he said. ``I can't seem to get away  
from it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990502.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 23:42:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doctor: Harris, Klebold Deadly Mix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Eric Harris was a troubled teen,  
apparently suffering from depression and obsession. Dylan Klebold 
was a follower, who was rejected by his peers and who found 
acceptance from Harris. 
</P>
<P>
	Psychologists say that was a deadly mix, exploding April 20 at  
Columbine High School when the pair marched through the school's 
halls, killing 13 of their classmates and then themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	``What leads to violence in kids is a series of problems:  
problems with the parents, a feeling of low self-esteem, a pattern 
of being rejected,'' said Dr. Jeff Dolgan, chief of psychology at 
Children's Hospital in Denver. ``These kids were in a group that 
was put down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harris, whose father retired to Colorado from the U.S. Air  
Force, railed against his tormentors on his Internet web page, 
saying ``we have many enemies in our school.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also warned of the attack that he planned for a year, saying  
``I don't care if I live or die in the shootout.'' The pair timed 
their assault for Adolf Hitler's birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	Just five days before the attack, the Marine Corps rejected  
Harris as a recruit because he had been taking the antidepressant 
drug Luvox. He also reportedly was turned down by a girl he wanted 
to take to the prom. An autopsy found no drugs -- illegal or 
prescription -- in his body. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Don Marxhausen, pastor of St. Philip Lutheran Church in  
Littleton and pastor for the Klebolds, said his daughters knew 
Harris as a young man filled with rage. He said Klebold, ``a nice 
young man with above-average intelligence,'' was easily pulled 
under Harris' spell. 
</P>
<P>
	``Harris was just so charismatic, but he was definitely angry,''  
Marxhausen said. ``There was just such a rage in Harris. You either 
had to follow him or get away from him,'' the pastor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris and Klebold found comfort and refuge in a group called  
the ``Trenchcoat Mafia,'' a group of about a dozen school outcasts 
who bought floor-length dusters at a western store sale for $99 
each. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the group were angry because ``jocks'' and other  
members of the school elite teased and harassed them, throwing 
rocks and cigarettes at them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everywhere they went, they were teased about how they  
dressed,'' Harris' former girlfriend, Tiffany Typher, told The 
Denver Post. ``If you're called a psycho all your life, you're 
going to live out that reputation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Friends said Klebold joined up with Harris about four years ago  
and began shunning his former friends. 
</P>
<P>
	``When Eric and Dylan got together, Eric changed Dylan's  
demeanor. Dylan was a follower, who was constantly looking for 
someone to lead,'' said Nick Baumgart, 17, a senior who met Dylan 
in grade school. 
</P>
<P>
	Klebold and Harris got their own home computers, and linked them  
with modems, playing simulated shooting games like ``Doom.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They had death matches with violent computer games, matching  
computer to computer,'' Baumgart said. ``I don't believe violent 
video games lead to violence, but this was different. They'd play 
these games for hours and hours and hours.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. John Kluck, a psychiatrist at the University of Colorado  
Health Sciences Center, said the youths did a good job of hiding 
their antisocial behavior from their parents and authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	Following their arrest on criminal trespass, theft and mischief  
charges, the two boys were ordered to perform community service and 
write apology letters. Harris' juvenile diversion supervisor wrote 
that the boy enjoyed his anger management class and he called him 
``a bright young man who is likely to succeed in life.'' 
Supervisors wrote that Klebold needed to work on his motivation. 
</P>
<P>
	``They played social roles so they didn't stand out to the  
judges or their parents,'' Kluck said. 
</P>
<P>
	Matt Good knew Harris, the schoolmate who lived in the gray,  
two-story home two doors down. He said Klebold often came over in 
his older BMW to visit Harris. 
</P>
<P>
	Matt, 16, now wonders about the explosions neighbors heard in a  
nearby meadow. But other than that, ``We never saw anything to be 
alarmed about,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Matt Good said Harris and Klebold spoke German to each other in  
the hallway and talked a lot about World War II, Hitler and the 
Nazis. ``He thought Eric was a little strange, and he didn't want 
to associate with him,'' said Matt's father, Mike Good. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Beard, a fellow student, said Harris came to class in  
steel-toed combat boots and a German cross. Harris was also said to 
be a big fan of Rammstein, a German industrial, or techno, rock 
band. 
</P>
<P>
	John House, 17, a senior, said he refused to associate with  
Klebold after he joined the Trenchcoat Mafia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went bowling with him, and when he would do something good,  
he would shout, `Heil Hitler!' and throw up his hand,'' House said. 
``It just made everyone mad.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
