<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dole Takes Centrist Gun Control View </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- A Republican quiz: In seven minutes or  
less, explain why you should be the party's presidential nominee 
instead of George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight GOP candidates faced that test Sunday night in speeches to  
New Hampshire party leaders. The Texas governor, meanwhile, 
remained at home in Austin -- unwilling to risk his front-runner 
status. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Dole answered with a challenge to the National Rifle  
Association on gun control, promising to be a tough-on-crime 
president ``no matter what the special interests say.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rival Steve Forbes replied that the country must ``resist the  
temptation to enact new laws'' in response to tragedies such as the 
school shooting in Littleton, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	The remarks were made at a dinner billed as the party's first  
major event of the 2000 campaign in this first-in-the-nation 
primary state. Candidates were given seven minutes to speak, with a 
band enforcing the time limit. 
</P>
<P>
	Three likely candidates stayed away: Arizona Sen. John McCain,  
commentator Pat Buchanan and Bush. McCain was celebrating his son's 
13th birthday; Buchanan was campaigning in Arizona; Bush has 
refused to campaign outside his state until the legislative session 
ends later this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	Many activists who attended the kickoff questioned or criticized  
Bush's decision to pass up the event, but most predicted it would 
not change his front-runner status. 
</P>
<P>
	For the rest of the field, the gathering offered a chance to  
shine outside Bush's shadow. Their goal is to emerge as alternative 
pick should he falter. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole's was the boldest attempt at creating news and drawing  
attention to her campaign. Wearing a clip-on microphone, the former 
American Red Cross president stood several feet from the podium -- 
spinning on her high heels to address the crowd that surrounded 
her. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she supports the continuation of the assault-weapons  
ban, elimination of bullets that pierce bulletproof vests and full 
federal funding of instant background checks for gun buyers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think you need an AK-47 (assault rifle) to defend your  
family,'' she said, receiving a smattering of polite applause. The 
reception was even cooler when Mrs. Dole, ranked second in most GOP 
presidential polls, said she supported child safety locks on 
handguns. 
</P>
<P>
	One person in the crowd booed. Few applauded.  
</P>
<P>
	Aides say they were not troubled by the reaction because Mrs.  
Dole is trying to expand the GOP's base by targeting moderate 
voters, not party regulars. President Clinton adopted a similar 
approach on gun control in 1996 to court moderate and independent 
voters, particularly women. 
</P>
<P>
	The other GOP candidates found other ways to set themselves  
apart. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Vice President Dan Quayle argued that he deserves the  
nomination. ``Who has been fighting for your values and your 
families for over 20 years?'' he asked. ``Who has the experience 
when it comes to foreign policy and who has been tested and has the 
courage to lead this great country of ours?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. John Kasich of Ohio portrayed himself as the candidate who  
would ease ``the frustrations of everyday working people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith, a native son with little chance of  
winning the nomination, bragged that he had voted to remove Clinton 
from office and criticized Republicans who didn't. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
