<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Captive Soldiers Reach Freedom  
</P>
<P>
	RAMSTEIN, Germany (AP) -- Three American servicemen arrived at a  
U.S. military base in Germany today, ending a month of captivity in 
Yugoslavia. Dressed in Army fatigues, the freed soldiers were 
exuberant and appeared healthy, standing tall and walking briskly. 
But they still showed signs of the cuts and bruises they suffered 
when captured on a patrol mission along the Macedonia-Yugoslav 
border on March 31. They were escorted to Ramstein by the Rev. 
Jesse Jackson, who arranged their release in Belgrade just hours 
earlier. 

</P>
<P>
	No End in Sight for Airstrikes  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Although President Clinton welcomed  
Yugoslavia's dramatic release today of three U.S. soldiers, his 
administration rebuffed Slobodan Milosevic's request for a pause in 
the airstrikes and for a meeting with the president until the Serb 
leader agrees to all NATO demands. ``This gesture ... of goodwill 
cannot obliterate or overcome the stench of evil and death that has 
been inflicted in those killing fields in Kosovo,'' Defense 
Secretary William Cohen said on NBC's ``Meet the Press.'' But the 
Russians, who have been seeking a diplomatic solution for weeks, 
won an audience with Clinton tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Premier To Meet With Clinton  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and Japanese Prime Minister  
Keizo Obuchi are expected to discuss trade disputes and the pace of 
Japan's economic reforms when they meet at the White House 
tomorrow. Clinton wants Obuchi to move quickly to revitalize 
Japan's economy in order to stabilize the rest of Asia. But Obuchi 
says he's doing his best and that it will take time to reverse 
Japan's worst recession in 50 years. Obuchi is making the first 
official U.S. visit of a Japanese prime minister in 12 years. 

</P>
<P>
	Alleged War Criminals in U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Despite evidence of serious human rights abuses,  
people from such countries as El Salvador and Haiti are living in 
the United States right under the noses of immigration officials 
and sometimes with help from the government, The Boston Globe 
reported today. ``It is really appalling to think that the United 
States has become the retirement home of choice for murderers and 
despots,'' said William Ford, a New York attorney whose sister Ita, 
a nun, was killed by members of the Salvadoran National Guard. 

</P>
<P>
	13 Dead in Arkansas Boat Accident  
</P>
<P>
	HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) -- The death toll from the sinking of a  
tourist boat rose to 13 today when a woman died in a hospital and 
divers returned to a lake and found her ex-husband's body. Their 
daughter also was among the victims. The amphibious vehicle of 
World War II vintage -- called a ``duck'' because it travels both on 
land and water -- sank rapidly shortly after entering Lake Hamilton 
yesterday while passengers panicked and scrambled for life 
preservers. Twenty-one people were on board, including the driver. 

</P>
<P>
	Colo. Students To Return To Class  
</P>
<P>
	MORRISON, Colo. (AP) -- A group of Columbine High School students  
today attended a final memorial service for the 15 people killed in 
the April 20 massacre. The gathering at the scenic Red Rocks 
amphitheater comes a day before they head back to class at nearby 
Chatfield High School, considered a rival. Columbine, still a 
massive crime scene, won't be reopened at least until fall. Some 
2,000 Columbine students will complete the year at Chatfield. 
Tomorrow, students will be given lapel ribbons with blue for 
Columbine and burgundy for Chatfield, bound together in the shape 
of a heart. 

</P>
<P>
	Grissom's Mercury Capsule Located  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Astronaut Gus Grissom's Mercury  
capsule was found over the weekend after it was lost at sea 38 
years ago. An underwater salvage team that had been searching for 
the spacecraft for nearly two weeks discovered the capsule. But 
Liberty Bell 7, the only U.S. spacecraft ever lost following a 
successful mission, is still 3 miles beneath the Atlantic's surface 
and about 300 miles offshore. Salvagers won't be able to recover 
the space craft for another few weeks because of problems with a 
vehicle used to identify the capsule. 

</P>
<P>
	Penguins Beat Devils 3-2  
</P>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Jaromir Jagr scored an electrifying tying goal  
with only 2:12 left in regulation, then won it in overtime as the 
Pittsburgh Penguins staved off playoff elimination by beating the 
New Jersey Devils 3-2 Sunday. The Penguins, on the verge not only 
of elimination but of possible extinction as the franchise's fate 
is being decided in bankruptcy court, now will play a Game 7 
Tuesday night in New Jersey. 

</P>
<P>
	Elway Officially Retires  
</P>
<P>
	ENGLEWOOD, Colo. (AP) -- Denver Broncos quarterback John Elway  
made his retirement official today after 16 years on the team. 
Elway guided the Broncos to more victories (148) than any other 
quarterback in NFL history. He threw for 51,475 yards and accounted 
for 54,882 total yards. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990502.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 04:45:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Former U.S. POWs Head Home  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Three U.S. soldiers held in  
captivity by Yugoslav authorities for more than a month were 
released and left the country earlier today. Holding hands with 
U.S. civil rights leader Jesse Jackson, they walked into 
neighboring Croatia chanting ``Free at last, free at last, thank 
God Almighty, free at last!'' Jackson negotiated their release. 
Amid huge smiles and a sense of jubilation in Belgrade, the 
soldiers embraced the U.S. civil rights leader, who said he hoped 
their release would lead to a diplomatic breakthrough in the Kosovo 
conflict. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Reports Plane Down in Adriatic  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- NATO said today a U.S. Marine Corps  
AV8B Harrier plane crashed in the Adriatic Sea yesterday while on a 
training mission for operations in the Balkans. The pilot was 
reported safety rescued. It was the second report of a crashed U.S. 
warplane in 24 hours operating over and around Yugoslavia. Hours 
earlier, the alliance said a U.S. F-16 fighter plane had gone down 
over western Serbia earlier today. The pilot of the aircraft was 
rescued by allied forces. The pilot, who ejected from the plane, 
was back at an allied base undergoing medical examination. 

</P>
<P>
	Arkansas Boat Accident Kills 11  
</P>
<P>
	HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) -- An amphibious tourist boat sank  
yesterday, drowning 11 people in a lake as panicked passengers 
scrambled for life preservers and nearby residents rushed to their 
boats to pluck victims from the choppy water. The open-air, World 
War II-vintage boat sank quickly on Lake Hamilton near this popular 
tourist town. A cloth canopy may have trapped the victims as the 
wheeled craft went down less than a mile offshore, Mayor Bob Mathis 
said. A survivor, Gary Ledin, said there was little time to react. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Attends Press Dinner  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton put aside any lingering  
bitterness and cracked a few jokes at the annual White House 
Correspondents Association dinner last night. Clinton showed up 
late enough to miss the presentation of an award to Newsweek's 
Michael Isikoff, a reporter who dedicated the past year to 
unearthing the Monica Lewinsky scandal. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Seeks Military Spending Boost  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican Rep. Robin Hayes, whose North  
Carolina district includes two major military bases, said yesterday 
that the Clinton administration has neglected defense spending and 
left the military's resources stretched too thin. In the weekly GOP 
radio address, Hayes said a smaller military has been called on to 
handle crises all over the globe, with the current action in 
Yugoslavia taking a further toll. 

</P>
<P>
	NRA Takes Stand Against Gun Laws  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Charlton Heston took a defiant stand against  
gun-control laws yesterday at the National Rifle Association's 
annual meeting in Denver, saying the NRA isn't the villain in the 
Colorado school shooting. While the gun lobby held its annual 
meeting, thousands of opponents circled outside. Officials of the 
nation's largest group of gun owners -- at 2.8 million members -- 
refused to cancel the meeting despite requests from Mayor 
Wellington Webb and other local officials. ``We will not be silent 
or be told, `Do not come here, you are not welcome in your own 
land,''' Heston said. 

</P>
<P>
	Duke KO'd in Livingston Race  
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Former Gov. Dave Treen and state Rep. David  
Vitter qualified yesterday for a May 29 runoff to replace Bob 
Livingston in the House. Former Ku Klux Klan leader David Duke ran 
third. While Treen and Vitter celebrated, Duke refused to concede 
and backed off earlier statements that this would be the end of his 
political career. 

</P>
<P>
	Philly Prison Alumni Hold Reunion  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Like high school chums with fond pasts to  
recall, former prisoners at one of Pennsylvania's oldest prisons 
returned yesterday with the jailers who once guarded for their own 
``alumni reunion.'' The first-ever such social event at the 
170-year-old, stone-walled Eastern State Prison gave all who once 
dwelled behind its foreboding walls a chance to swap stories about 
their time at the prison. 

</P>
<P>
	96-Year-Old Sets World Running Mark  
</P>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- A 96-year-old man shattered an age-group world  
record yesterday when he ran the 100-meter dash in 24.01 seconds. 
Erwin Jaskulski of Honolulu broke the 95-and-older age-group record 
of 38.82 seconds set by Kazuhiko Tsutsumi of Japan in 1997, said 
officials at the Punahou Relays. 

</P>
<P>
	Suns Win To Make Playoffs  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Tom Gugliotta had 24 points and 12 rebounds and  
Rex Chapman, wearing protective goggles over his injured eye, added 
20 points last night as the Phoenix Suns clinched their 11th 
consecutive playoff berth with a 107-77 victory over the Vancouver 
Grizzlies. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
