<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Denver Fans Accept Elway's Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- It was time.  
</P>
<P>
	Although Denver Broncos' fans had dreaded the day, most  
reluctantly agreed Sunday it was time for legendary quarterback 
John Elway to leave the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not disappointed,'' said David Hill of Denver. ``I don't  
think you can ask for anything better than what he has done for 
us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For 16 years, Elway, 38, has been entertaining fans with pass  
after pass, heart-stopping, come-from-behind victories, jaunty runs 
into the end zone and a toothy grin. 
</P>
<P>
	And, of course, two straight Super Bowl victories.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a bummer,'' said John Woodmansee of Denver, who sat on a  
bench, enjoying a quiet afternoon in Larimer Square. ``We think one 
more year, he could have done that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, he reflected, ``I guess when you're done, you're done. And  
I definitely respect that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elway delayed the official announcement of his retirement  
because of the Columbine High School shootings that left a dozen 
students, a teacher and two student gunmen dead. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, Elway has been troubled by injuries, including  
an arthritic left knee that probably will have to be replaced. Last 
year, he missed all or part of six games because of hamstring, back 
and rib injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	With that in mind, most fans thought it best for the future Hall  
of Famer to leave a winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Stephen Young of Denver wanted Elway to help the team to  
a third consecutive Super Bowl victory, even if he could have 
played just a few of the games. ``It's going to be tough (for the 
team next season),'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	His favorite Elway memory is of The Drive in 1986, when Elway  
took the Broncos 98 yards for a tying touchdown in the final 
minutes before defeating Cleveland in overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	Young's wife, Leslie, said she understood Elway's decision.  
``With things the way they are in Denver, maybe it's just time,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	For Hill, favorite memories range from an Elway run that ended  
in a tackle that spun him like a helicopter in Super Bowl XXXII to 
the quarterback's community leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	``From a professional athlete's standpoint, he's a wonderful  
role model,'' Hill said. ``I'm very happy for him and his family 
who can go on about their lives and live like you and I can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For his part, Elway said he's not going anywhere. He has firm  
roots in the Denver area now, has his name on a string of auto 
dealerships and there has been speculation about a future in 
politics or broadcasting. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said he will be the team's biggest fan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
