<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Surgery in Womb Saves Lives of Twins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Lisa Bailey was 19 weeks pregnant with  
identical twins when her doctor in Oklahoma City darkened an 
ultrasound screen and gave her heartbreaking news: One twin was 
robbing the other of life. 
</P>
<P>
	The watery sac protecting one child had collapsed like shrink  
wrap. Inside it, movement was faint. The other fetus was big, 
active and well-cushioned in fluid. If nothing was done, chances 
were one would shrivel; the other would become overwhelmed. Mrs. 
Bailey could lose one fetus, or both. 
</P>
<P>
	The prognosis was poor.  
</P>
<P>
	Then she learned of a selective endoscopic procedure pioneered  
by Dr. Ruben Quintero, a fetal surgeon in Tampa. He used a tiny 
doll-sized optical instrument to penetrate the amniotic sac of the 
plump twin. In utero, he traced and selectively lasered culprit 
vessels that prevented the deprived twin from getting the nutrients 
needed to survive. 
</P>
<P>
	Eleven weeks later, the smaller twin had nearly caught up in  
size. One was 2 pounds 13 ounces; the other was 2 pounds 11 ounces, 
Mrs. Bailey said. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent stress test showed that the twins were doing well.  
``Their little hearts are beating fine. We're so thankful,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``And they're moving around like acrobats,'' added her husband,  
Keith Bailey. 
</P>
<P>
	At the University of Oklahoma, Dr. John R. Stanley III, who  
specializes in high-risk pregnancies, told the couple their options 
were few. There was a hallmark surgical technique -- selective laser 
surgery -- but he didn't know much about it. They could research it 
on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were shocked, numb,'' Mrs. Bailey said at learning her  
twins were in jeopardy. ``We waited 17 years to have children and 
we wanted our two boys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Baileys didn't have access to the Internet. So friends  
gathered the data. The couple read up. They paged Quintero. Within 
10 minutes he called them. They were on the phone with the 
perinatologist for 45 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Quintero canceled a trip to Venezuela. Within a few days the  
Baileys flew to Tampa. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the week was over, their fears had turned to hope -- Mrs.  
Bailey had every expectation of delivering two healthy sons in 
early July. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is my miracle,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Inside her were two strong heartbeats. The bladder on the puny  
baby was working, refilling the dry amniotic sac. Three liters of 
fluid had been drained from the sac of the larger twin, fluid that 
wouldn't return. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm so glad we went to Florida,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	In February, when she arrived in Tampa less than five months  
pregnant, swelling and fluid buildup left Mrs. Bailey looking and 
feeling like she was eight months along. The babies were a mere six 
or seven ounces each. 
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't breathe,'' she said. ``It was like when you blow up  
a ball too tight,'' her husband said. 
</P>
<P>
	She credits Quintero, who works at St. Joseph's Women's  
Hospital, with saving the lives of her boys against the odds: She 
is 35 years old, a first-time mother-to-be, carrying twins, and her 
high-risk pregnancy was in trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	The disease is called twin-twin transfusion syndrome (TTTS), a  
condition affecting 10 percent of the identical twins in utero. 
</P>
<P>
	Each case has a donor twin and a recipient twin, the dichotomy  
created by an unbalanced blood flow between identical twins sharing 
a common placenta. 
</P>
<P>
	When the vascular system is healthy, the blood travels to the  
placenta via the arteries, picks up oxygen and nutrients and 
returns to each fetus via the veins. 
</P>
<P>
	In diseased cases, the vascular systems are altered. Some  
arteries deliver the blood of the donor twin to the placenta, but 
the veins return the blood to the recipient twin instead of the 
donor. 
</P>
<P>
	Without surgery, both babies could die. Previously, surgeons  
severed all vessels crossing the membrane dividing the amniotic 
sacs to stop the piracy. 
</P>
<P>
	Quintero believed there had to be another way, a way to pinpoint  
problem vessels and sever only those. Such a selective technique 
would leave intact other vessels essential to fetal survival, 
vessels that carry oxygen and nutrients. 
</P>
<P>
	Quintero built on the work of Dr. Julian DeLia, a fetal surgeon  
from Milwaukee, and others before him who took on the task of 
trying to surgically intervene in similar cases of aberrant 
identical twin development in utero. 
</P>
<P>
	And he came up with a selective endoscopic procedure to operate  
within the womb. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dr. Quintero pioneeded endoscopic fetal surgery. He was the  
first person in the history of surgery to operate on a human fetus 
through an endoscope,'' said Dr. Roberto Romero, chief of the 
perinatology branch of the National Institute of Child Health and 
Human Development in Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a landmark advance,'' Romero said. In earlier  
procedures Romero said a fetus was accessed through an abdominal 
incision and an open uterus creating a high rate of complications. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Frank Manning, a Bronx, N.Y., obstetrician-gynecologist  
specializing in maternal-fetal health, said Quintero's work wasn't 
scientifically original, but added that the Florida surgeon 
developed his own variations and a better way to find vessels. 
</P>
<P>
	``I claim originality,'' said Quintero. ``I spent three years  
trying to find a way to find the vessels.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quintero used miniature instruments: an endoscope smaller than a  
pencil to look into the womb, and a needle about the size of one 
used to draw blood to sheath the endoscope. 
</P>
<P>
	The precision and clarity of the pictures transmitted through  
the endoscope were so detailed Quintero could see everything from 
tiny fingers to minute organs. 
</P>
<P>
	Painstakingly, the surgeon tracked each blood vessel and blunted  
certain ones using the minimally invasive procedure. It left a tiny 
incision a bandage was able to cover. 
</P>
<P>
	``With previous techniques, there was nothing that clearly says  
these are the vessels that allow blood sharing and these don't,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The technique changed the odds of survival.  
</P>
<P>
	``It went from almost 100 percent likelihood of losing the  
pregnancy if nothing were done, to at least 80 percent chance one 
twin would survive and 50 percent chance the two would survive,'' 
Quintero said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The important thing is for people to know there is hope that  
we can stop the disease, that we can turn this around,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Quintero came to Tampa in October 1996 from Wayne State  
University in Detroit. He introduced his technique four years 
earlier at the university's Hutzel Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Bailey has had sonograms weekly since Quintero performed  
the procedure and said ``each time it's just gotten better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Terminating the pregnancy was not an option,'' explained her  
husband, a 41-year-old businessman. ``Sacrificing one for the other 
wasn't either,'' added Mrs. Bailey, a representative for a 
California fragrance company. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have passed the first threshold and are hoping for a  
storybook ending,'' said Bailey. 
</P>
<P>
	The names of the babies? Dillon and Ryan. The Baileys had the  
names picked out from the start. Ironically, the first letters also 
stand for donor and recipient. 
</P>
</TEXT>
